Here are 7 tips from the Prophet (Sallalahu 'alayhi wa salam) to save yourself from Hellfire. 1) Performing 4 rak'aat before 'Duhr' and 4 after it Umm Habibah the wife of the Prophet (Sallalahu 'alayhi wa salam) : She heard Allah's Messenger (Sallahu 'alayhi wa salam) saying :"Whoever maintains four Rak'aat before Zuhr and four after it, Allah makes him prohibited for the Fire." [ Sunan At-Tirmidhi 428, Grade : Sahih (authentic) ] PS : According to the scholars, the 4 rak'aat should be performed by 2 prayers of 2 rak'aat. 2) Fasting The Prophet (Sallalahu 'alayhi wa salam) said : "Whoever fasts a day in the way of Allah, then Allah will move his face away from the Hellfire by a distance of seventy years". [ Sahih Bukhari , Muslim ] PS : Try to fast some mondays and thursdays outside Ramadan in order to get further away from Hellfire in Shaa Allah. 3) Making a du'aa which will make Paradise and Hellfire supplicate for the believers The Prophet (Sallalahu 'alayhi wa salam) said :"Whoever asks Allah for Paradise three times, Paradise will say: O Allah, admit him into Paradise. Whoever seeks protection from Hellfire three times, Hellfire will say: O Allah, save him from the Hellfire.” [ Sunan At-Tirmidhi 2572, Grade : Sahih (authentic) according to Al-Albani ] The following dua'a are : *Allahuma adkhilni Jannat ul Firdaws ( 3 times ) *Allahuma ajirni minan naar ( 3 times ) PS : Try to say these du'aas in every prayers 4) Whoever has faith, prays and fasts will enter Paradise whether he fights in Jihad or not Abu Huraira reported : The Prophet (Sallalahu 'alayhi wa salam) said : "Whoever believes in Allah and His Messenger, establishes prayer, and fasts the month of Ramadan will have a right upon Allah that he will be entered into Paradise whether he strives in the cause of Allah or remains in the land in which he was born.” [ Sahih Bukhari 2790 ] 5) Having a good behaviour The Prophet (Sallalahu 'alayhi wa salam) said :"Shall I not tell you for whom the Hellfire is forbidden? It is every person accessible, polite, and mild.” [ Sunan At-Tirmidhi 2488, Grade : Hasan ] PS : It means he is accessible to people, he is against harshness, easy-going in his character and generous in his personality. 6) Giving charity According to Ady Ibn Hatim (may Allah be pleased with him), the Prophet (Sallalahu 'alayhi wa salam) said : "Guard yourself from the Hellfire even with half of a date in charity. If he cannot find it, then with a kind word."[ Sahih Bukhari 1417 and Sahih Muslim 1016 ] 7) Crying out of fear of Allah It was narrated that Abu Hurayrah (may Allah be pleased with him) said: The Messenger of Allah (Sallalahu 'alayhi wa salam) said: “A man who weeps for fear of Allah will not enter Hell until the milk goes back into the udder, and dust produced (when fighting) for the sake of Allah and the smoke of Hell will never coexist.” [Jami' at-Tirmidhi 1633] PS : The last part of the hadith is a metaphor for it being impossible, as in the verse where Allah says (interpretation of the meaning): “and they will not enter Paradise until the camel goes through the eye of the needle” [7:40]. Share this with others so that you gain as much rewards as them practising. May Allah save us from Hellfire. Ameen.

The prevalent misconception is that we are living in Kali Yuga. In the book "Holy Science" written by Swami Yukteshwar Giri, the Kali Yuga ended in 1499, and Dwapara Yuga started. The mistake was that yugas are a 24,000 year cycle, not 4320000 year cycle. The mistake crept at the beginning of Kali Yuga, when King Yudhisthira took all of his learned court and retired to the Himalayas, leaving no expert to perform the correct calculations. If we were still in Kali Yuga, finer mysteries of nature like electricity and gravitation, would be incomprehensible to mankind. Instead, we are progressing at the speed light with the internet and will soon see commercial space travel.

As someone who understands the Hindu teachings of non-duality, there can be no possibility of time travel since time doesn’t exist in our reality or experience. What human beings perceive or experience of time is nothing more then a concept in their head of artificial time based upon measurements of day and night cycles and changes of the seasons. From that information we create measurements like seconds, minutes, hours, days, weeks, months, years etc. But time only exists that way when you are thinking about it. So it only exists in one’s mind. The only time that exists is the present as in Now. For time to exist in the way we think of it as artificial time, there would have to be a past and future, which there isn’t. Nobody has ever experienced the past or the future, all anyone has ever experienced is Now. Don’t take my word for it look to your own experience. Have you ever experienced the past or the future? Have you ever escaped Now? As far as time itself is concerned it is eternally Now and that is it.

The Hindu metrics of time (Kaala Vyavahara) can be summarized as below: • a Lipta (लिप्ता) is approximately 0.4 seconds • a Vighati (विघटि) is 60 Liptas, or approximately 24 seconds • a Ghadika (घटि) is 60 Vighatis, or approximately 24 minutes • a Muhurta is equal to 2 Ghadikas, or approximately 48 minutes • a Nakshatra ahoratram (नक्षत्र अहोरत्रम्) or sidereal day is exactly equal to 30 Muhurtas (Note: A day is considered to begin and end at sunrise, not midnight.) An alternate system described in the Vishnu Purana Time measurement section of the Vishnu Purana Book I Chapter III is as follows: 100 Truti = 1 Tatpara 30 Tatpara = 1 Nimesha 15 Nimeshas = 1 Kásht́há 30 Kásht́hás = 1 Kalá 30 Kalás = 1 Kṣaṇa 12 Kṣaṇa = 1 Muhúrtta 30 Muhúrttas = 1 day (24 hours) 30 days = 1 month 6 months = 1 Ayana 2 Ayanas = 1 year or one day (day + night) of the gods Small units of time used in the Vedas • a Trasarenu is the combination of 6 celestial atoms. • a Truti is the time needed to integrate 3 Trasarenus, or 1/1687.5th of a second. • a Vedha is 100 Trutis. • a Lava is 3 Vedhas. • a Nimesha is 3 Lavas, or a blink. • a Kshanas is 3 Nimeshas. • a Kashthas is 5 Kshanas, or about 8 seconds. • a Laghu is 15 Kashthas, or about 2 minutes. 15 Laghus make one Nadika, which is also called a danda. This equals the time before water overflows in a six-pala-weight [fourteen ounce] pot of copper, in which a hole is bored with a gold probe weighing four masha and measuring four fingers long. The pot is then placed on water for calculation. 2 Dandas make one Muhurta. 6 or 7 Dandas make one Yamah, or 1/4th of a day or night. 4 Praharas or 4 Yamas are in each day or each night. LUNAR METRICS a tithi (also spelled thithi ) or lunar day is defined as the time it takes for the longitudinal angle between the moon and the sun to increase by 12°. Tithis begin at varying times of day and vary in duration from approximately 19 to approximately 26 hours. a paksa (also paksha) or lunar fortnight consists of 15 tithis a masa or lunar month (approximately 29.5 days) is divided into 2 pakshas: the one between new moon and full moon is called gaura (bright) or shukla paksha; the one between full moon and new moon krishna paksha a ritu is 2 masa an ayanam is 3 rituhs a year is 2 Aayanas TROPICAL METRICS a Yaama (याम) = 1/4th of a day(light) or night [ = 7½ Ghatis (घटि) = 3¾ Muhurtas (मुहूर्त) = 3 Horas (होरा) ] 4 Yaamas 1 half of the day (either day or night) 8 Yaamas 1 day (day + night) an Ahoratram is a tropical day (Note: A day is considered to begin and end at sunrise, not midnight.) Reckoning of time among other entities Reckoning of time amongst the pitrs. 1 human day = 1/30 day of the pitrs 30 days of human is 1 month of human = 1 day of the pitrs 12 months of human = 1 year of the pitrs The lifespan of the pitrs is 100 years of the pitrs (= 3,600 human years) Reckoning of time amongst the Devas. 1 human year = 1 day of the Devas. 30 days of the Devas = 1 month of the Devas. 12 months of the Devas = 1 year of the Devas The lifespan of the Devas is 100 years of the Devas (= 36,000 human years) The Vishnu Purana Time measurement section of the Vishnu Purana Book I Chapter III explains the above as follows: 2 Ayanas (six month periods, see above) = 1 year or one day (day + night) of the devas 360 days of the devas = 1 year of the devas 12,000 years of the devas = 4 Yugas Reckoning of time for Brahma. 12,000 years of the Devas = 1 day of Brahma (4320,000,000 human years). This day is divided into 10, 000 parts called charanas. The charanas are divided as follows: The Four Yugas 4 charanas (1,728,000 solar years) Satya Yuga 3 charanas(1,296,000 solar years) Treta Yuga 2 charanas(864,000 solar years) Dwapara Yuga 1 charanas(432,000 solar years) Kali Yuga The cycle repeats itself so altogether there are 1000 cycles of yugas in one day of Brahma. One cycle of the above four yugas is one mahayuga (4.32 billion solar years) A manvantara consists of 71 mahayugas (306,720,000 solar years). Each Manvantara is ruled by a Manu. After each manvantara follows one Sandhi Kala of the same duration as a Krita Yuga (1,728,000 = 4 Charana). (It is said that during a Sandhi Kala, the entire earth is submerged in water.) A kalpa consists of a period of 1,728,000 solar years called Adi Sandhi, followed by 14 manvantaras and Sandhi Kalas. A day of Brahma equals (14 times 71 mahayugas) + (15 x 4 Charanas) = 994 mahayugas + (60 Charanas) = 994 mahayugas + (6 x 10) Charanas = 994 mahayugas + 6 mahayugas = 1000 mahayugas as is confirmed by the Gita statement "sahasra-yuga paryantam ahar-yad brahmano viduH", meaning, a day of brahma is of 1000 (maha-)yugas. Thus a day of Brahma, kalpa, is of duration: 4.32 billion solar years. Two kalpas constitute a day and night of Brahma 30 days of Brahma = 1 month of Brahma (259,200,000,000 human years) 12 months of Brahma = 1 year of Brahma (3,110,400,000,000 human years) 25 years of Brahma = 1 kalpa (77,760,000,000,000 human years) 2 kalpas = 1 parardha (155,520,000,000,000 human years) 2 parardhas = 100 years of Brahma, the lifespan of Brahma (311,040,000,000,000 human years) The Vishnu Purana Time measurement section of the Vishnu Purana Book I Chapter III explains the above as follows: 360 days of the gods = 1 year of the gods 12,000 years of the gods = 4 Yugas 1,000 sets of 4 Yugas = a day of Brahmá 50 years of Brahma = 1 Pararddham 100 years of Brahma = 1 Param 4,000 + 400 + 400 = 4,800 years = 1 Krita Yuga 3,000 + 300 + 300 = 3,600 years = 1 Tretá Yuga 2,000 + 200 + 200 = 2,400 years = 1 Dwápara Yuga 1,000 + 100 + 100 = 1,200 years = 1 Kali Yuga Alternately, the reigns of 7 Rishis, Indra and Manu = 1 Manwantara = 71x12,000+A (A is not given) = 852,000 years of the gods+A (A is not given) 14 Manwantaras = a day of Brahmá VEDIC TIME UNITS GREATER THAN A KALPA Ancient vedic cosmology takes into account handful of time spans which are even greater than one Kalpa or a day of Brahma. One such unit is a "Maha-Kalpa" which is composed of 36000 such days of Brahma. One Maha-Kalpa is considered as the lifetime of Brahma. There are time units which are larger than one Maha-Kalpa. The largest of them has been calculated as several quadrillions of human years. This precise and massive calculations indicate one important aspect of vedic time system, that, whenever the term "Infinity" has been mentioned in Vedas, it does not indicate something very large. Instead, it appears that the term is meant to refer its literal synonym itself.

Well it's written in the quran that the Earth was created before any of the stars in the universe which certainly is wrong cause as we know today that the oldest star in the whole universe is the methuselah star which is also known as HD 140283. Now this star is at least 13 billion years old and it's 200 light years away from us. And the Earth's age as we know today is 4.5 billion years old. So the Earth is at least 3 times younger than the oldest star in the universe. Now if you're wondering where does the Quran say that the Earth is older than all the stars of the universe, well then here you go Quran chapter 41 verse 9-12 the Quran says "Say, "Do you indeed disbelieve in He who created the earth in two days and attribute to Him equals? That is the Lord of the worlds." And He placed on the earth firmly set mountains over its surface, and He blessed it and determined therein its [creatures'] sustenance in four days without distinction - for [the information] of those who ask. Then He directed Himself to the heaven while it was smoke and said to it and to the earth, "Come [into being], willingly or by compulsion." They said, "We have come willingly." And He completed them as seven heavens within two days and inspired in each heaven its command. And We adorned the nearest heaven with lamps and as protection. That is the determination of the Exalted in Might, the Knowing." So as you can see, in these verses your Allah is clearly saying that he created the Earth before he created the stars of this universe by saying that he set lamps(stars) in the nearest heaven(Universe) after he's done creating the Earth. So yeah in these verses Allah is clearly saying that the Earth is older than even the oldest star in the whole universe. By the way there's one more mistake that I noticed is that the Quran says that plants can survive without the sun light by saying that he determined the existence of life on Earth before he created any star in the universe. As we all know the sun is also a star. So by saying that the Earth was created before stars, the Quran is also saying that the Earth was created even before the sun was. And since the Quran is saying that Allah determined the existence of life on Earth before he created the stars as Allah said "He blessed it and determined therein its [creatures'] sustenance in four days without distinction" the Quran is saying that plants were created on Earth even before the sun. Since plants have life too. That being said, the Quran's indicating that plants can survive without the sun light which certainly isn't correct. Cause we all know that plant's require the sunlight in order to survive and if you wanna test it then go buy some plants, take it home and keep it in a place where it's always completely dark and see what happens after probably 2 or 3 weeks. Trust me, the plants will die because of not getting the sun light. Alright that's all but yeah there are a lot more errors in the Quran that I've found but nah I ain't gonna mention them here. Cause I've been writing for quite a long time now. So yeah that's all.

Athkar that have great rewards ‎1- لَا إِلَهَ إِلاَّ اللَّهُ وَحْدَهُ لَا شَرِيكَ لَهُ، لَهُ الْمُلْكُ وَلَهُ الْحَمْدُ، وَهُوَ عَلَى كُلِّ شَيْءٍ قَدِيرٌ، سُبْحاَنَ اللَّهِ، وَالْحَمْدُ لِلَّهِ، وَلاَ إِلَهَ إِلاَّ اللَّهُ وَاللَّهُ أَكْبَرُ، وَلاَ حَوْلَ وَلاَ قُوَّةَ إِلاَّ بِاللَّهِ الْعَلِيِّ الْعَظِيمِ، رَبِّ اغْفِرْ لِي There is none worth of worship but Allah alone, Who has no partner, His is the dominion and to Him belongs all praise, and He is able to do all things. Glory is to Allah. Praise is to Allah. There is none worth of worship but Allah. Allah is the Most Great. There is no might and no power except by Allah's leave, the Exalted, the Mighty. My Lord, forgive me. (Whoever says this will be forgiven, and if he supplicates Allah, his prayer will be answered; if he performs ablution and prays, his prayer will be accepted.) ‎2- اللَّهُمَّ أَنْتَ رَبِّي لَّا إِلَهَ إِلَّا أَنْتَ، خَلَقْتَنِي وَأَنَا عَبْدُكَ، وَأَنَا عَلَى عَهْدِكَ وَوَعْدِكَ مَا اسْتَطَعْتُ، أَعُوذُ بِكَ مِنْ شَرِّ مَا صَنَعْتُ، أَبُوءُ لَكَ بِنِعْمَتِكَ عَلَيَّ، وَأَبُوءُ بِذَنْبِي فَاغْفِر لِي فَإِنَّهُ لَا يَغْفِرُ الذُّنُوبَ إِلَّا أَنْتَ O Allah, You are my Lord, there is none worthy of worship but You. You created me and I am your slave. I keep Your covenant, and my pledge to You so far as I am able. I seek refuge in You from the evil of what I have done. I admit to Your blessings upon me, and I admit to my misdeeds. Forgive me, for there is none who may forgive sins but You.(Whoever recites this with conviction in the evening and dies during that night shall enter Paradise, and whoever recites it with conviction in the morning and dies during that day shall enter Paradise.) ‎3- اللَّهُمَّ عَافِـني فِي بَدَنِي، اللَّهُمَّ عَافِـنِي فِي سَمْعِي، اللَّهُمَّ عَافِنِي فِي بَصَرِي، لَا إِلَهَ إلاَّ أَنْتَ. اللَّهُمَّ إِنِّي أَعُوذُبِكَ مِنَ الْكُفْر، وَالفَقْرِ، وَأَعُوذُبِكَ مِنْ عَذَابِ الْقَبْرِ ، لَا إلَهَ إلاَّ أَنْتَ O Allah, make me healthy in my body. O Allah, preserve for me my hearing. O Allah, preserve for me my sight. There is none worthy of worship but You. O Allah, I seek refuge in You from disbelief and poverty and I seek refuge in You from the punishment of the grave. There is none worthy of worship but You. (Three times) ‎4- حَسْبِيَ اللَّهُ لَآ إِلَهَ إِلَّا هُوَ عَلَيْهِ تَوَكَّلْتُ وَهُوَ رَبُّ الْعَرْشِ الْعَظِيمِ Allah is sufficient for me. There is none worthy of worship but Him. I have placed my trust in Him, He is Lord of the Majestic Throne. (Seven times)(Allah will grant whoever recites this Seven times in the morning or evening whatever he desires from this world or the next.) ‎5- اللَّهُمَّ إِنِّي أَسْأَلُكَ الْعَفْوَ وَالْعَافِيَةَ فِي الدُّنْيَا وَالْآخِرَةِ، اللَّهُمَّ إِنِّي أَسْأَلُكَ الْعَفْوَ وَالْعَافِيَةَ فِي دِينِي، وَدُنْيَايَ، وَأَهْلِي، وَمَالِي، اللَّهُمَّ اسْتُرْ عَوْرَاتِي، وَآمِنْ رَوْعَاتِي، اللَّهُمَّ احْفَظْنِي مِنْ بَيْنِ يَدَيَّ، وَمِنْ خَلْفِي، وَعَنْ يَمِينِي، وَعَنْ شِمَالِي، وَمِنْ فَوْقِي، وَأَعُوذُ بِعَظَمَتِكَ أَنْ أُغْتَالَ مِنْ تَحْتِيَ O Allah, I seek Your forgiveness and Your protection in this world and the next. O Allah, I seek Your forgiveness and Your protection in my religion, in my worldly affairs, in my family and in my wealth. O Allah, conceal my secrets and preserve me from anguish. O Allah, guard me from what is in front of me and behind me, from my left, and from my right, and from above me. I seek refuge in Your Greatness from being struck down from beneath me. ‎6- اللَّهُمَّ عَالِمَ الْغَيْبِ وَالشَّهَادَةِ فَاطِرَ السَّماوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضِ، رَبَّ كُلِّ شَيْءٍ وَمَلِيكَهُ، أَشْهَدُ أَنْ لَا إِلَهَ إِلَّا أَنْتَ، أَعُوذُ بِكَ مِنْ شَرِّ نَفْسِي، وَمِنْ شَرِّ الشَّيْطَانِ وَشِرْكِهِ، وَأَنْ أَقْتَرِفَ عَلَى نَفْسِي سُوءاً أَوْ أَجُرَّهُ إِلَى مُسْلِمٍ O Allah, Knower of the unseen and the evident , Maker of the heavens and the earth, Lord of everything and its Possessor, I bear witness that there is none worthy of worship but You. I seek refuge in You from the evil of my soul and from the evil of Satan and his helpers. (I seek refuge in You) from bringing evil upon my soul and from harming any Muslim. ‎7- رَضِيتُ باللَّهِ رَبًّا، وَبِالْإِسْلَامِ دِيناً، وَبِمُحَمَّدٍ صَلَى اللَّهُ عَلِيهِ وَسَلَّمَ نَبِيَّاً I am pleased with Allah as my Lord, with Islam as my religion and with Muhammad (peace and blessings of Allah be upon him) as my Prophet. (Three times)(Allah has promised that anyone who says every morning or evening will be pleased on the Day of Resurrection.) ‎8- يَاحَيُّ، يَا قَيُّومُ، بِرَحْمَتِكَ أَسْتَغِيثُ، أَصْلِحْ لِي شَأْنِي كُلَّهُ، وَلَا تَكِلْنِي إِلَى نَفْسِي طَرْفَةَ عَيْنٍ O Ever Living One, O Eternal One, by Your mercy I call on You to set right all my affairs. Do not place me in charge of my soul even for the blinking of an eye. ‎9- سُبْحَانَ اللَّهِ وَبِحَمْدِهِ Glory is to Allah and praise is to Him. (100 times)(Whoever recites this one hundred times in the morning and in the evening will not be surpassed on the Day of Resurrection by anyone having done better than this except for someone who had recited it more.) ‎10- لَا إِلَهَ إِلَّا اللَّهُ وَحْدَهُ لَا شَرِيكَ لَهُ، لَهُ الْمُلْكُ وَلَهُ الْحَمْدُ، وَهُوَ عَلَى كُلِّ شَيْءٍ قَدِيرٌ None has the right to be worshiped but Allah alone, Who has no partner. His is the dominion and His is the praise and He is Able to do all things. (10 times or once if tired.) ‎11- لَا إِلَهَ إِلَّا اللَّهُ وَحْدَهُ لَا شَرِيكَ لَهُ، لَهُ الْمُلْكُ وَلَهُ الْحَمْدُ، وَهُوَ عَلَى كُلِّ شَيْءٍ قَدِيرٌ None has the right to be worshiped but Allah alone, Who has no partner. His is the dominion and His is the praise and He is Able to do all things. (100 times in in the morning.)(Whoever recites this hundred times in the morning, Allah swt will reward him of freeing ten slaves, Allah will write one hundred Hasanat and and forgive him one hundred misdeeds and be protected from Satan until evening.) ‎12- سُبْحَانَ اللَّهِ وَبِحَمْدِهِ عَدَدَ خَلْقِهِ، وَرِضَا نَفْسِهِ، وَزِنَةَ عَرْشِهِ وَمِدَادَ كَلِمَاتِهِ Glory is to Allah and praise is to Him, by the multitude of His creation, by His Pleasure, by the weight of His Throne, and by the extent of His Words. (Three times in the morning.) ‎13- اللَّهُمَّ صَلِّ وَسَلَّمْ عَلَى نَبِيِّنَا مُحَمَّدٍ Oh Allah, we ask you for peace and blessings upon our prophet Muhammad. BENEFITS OF ISTIGHFAR ►Istighfar removes anxiety and Du'as are answered. ►Istighfar opens the door of sustenance. ►Istighfar opens the door of mercy. ►Istighfar opens the door of knowledge. ►Istighfar is also gateway of productivity ! ►Istighfar relieves you when you feel that sadness within you, when you are disturbed and frustrated, and also when anxiety surrounds you. Always say Astaghfirullah Astaghfirullah… ~~Don’t leave Istighfar A man once came to al-Hasan al-Basri and complained to him: “The sky does not shower us with rain.” He replied: “Seek Allah’s forgiveness (i.e. say أستغفر ألله).” Then another person came to him and said, “I complain of poverty.” He replied: “Seek Allah’s forgiveness.” Then another person came to him and complained, “My wife is barren; she cannot bear children.” He replied: “Seek Allah’s forgiveness.” The people who were present, said to al-Hasan: “Everytime a person came to you complaining, you instructed them to seek Allah’s forgiveness?” Al-Hasan al-Basri said, “Have you not read the statement of Allah? ‘I said “ Ask forgiveness of your Lord. Truly He is Oft-Forgiving. He will send rain to you in abundance; increase you in wealth and children; grant you gardens and bestow on you rivers.”‘” [Nuh (71):10-12] There are two things in the earth that give a person safety and security from the punishment of Allah. The first has been removed, whilst the second still remains. As for the first, it was the Messenger of Allah (peace be upon him). “Allah would not punish them while you were among them.” [al-Anfal (8):33] As for the second, it is istighfar. “Allah would not punish them as long as they sought forgiveness.” [al-Anfal (8):33] أستغفر ألله… أستغفر ألله… أستغفر ألله… Do not ever leave istighfar! Please share and remember that you will receive the reward for all those who make istighfar, due to your reminder. Astaghfirullaaha wa ‘atoobu ‘ilayhi. I seek the forgiveness of Allah and repent to Him. (Recite one hundred times during the day) It was reported in Saheeh Muslim that Prophet Muhammad (S.A.W.) said: “I seek forgiveness one hundred times in a day.” [Muslim] Du'a for seeking forgiveness: Dua of Prophet Adam (A.S.) Rabbana zalamna anfusana wa in lam taghfirlana watar hamna lana koonanna minal khasireen [7:23] ”Our Lord ! we have sinned against ourselves and unless You grant us forgiveness and bestow Your mercy upon us, we shall most certainly be lost." رَبَّنا ظَلَمنا أَنفُسَنا وَإِن لَم تَغفِر لَنا وَتَرحَمنا لَنَكونَنَّ مِنَ الخٰسِرينَ [SURAH AL-A`RAF, VERSE 23] Du'a of Yunus (A.S) repenting to Allah in the belly of the whale: “ LAA ILAAHA ILLAA ANTA SUBHAANAKA INNY KUNTU MINATHAULIMEEN” [21:87] “There is none worthy of worship except You. You are pure. Verily I am amongst the oppressors.” [Al-‘Anbya’ 87] Prophet Muhammad (Peace and Blessings be upon him) said about the Invocation of Yunus “None who is experiencing difficulty employs it except that Allah would relieve him of his difficulty.” [At-Tirmidhi] Nooh (A.S) asked for the forgiveness of Allaah The Almighty, repenting by saying: Rabbi Inneee A-o’od’u Bika An As-alaka Maa Laysa Lee Bihee I’lm Wa Illaa Taghfirlee Wa Tarh’amneee Akum Minal Khaasireen [11:47] “My Lord, I seek refuge in You from asking that of which I have no knowledge. And unless You forgive me and have mercy upon me, I will be among the losers.” (Surat Hūd, 11: 47) We must recite this dua’a to have full faith in the wisdom of Allah under all good and bad circumstances because Allah is all-knowing; and humbly seek His help to keep ourselves on the right path. Say: Allahumma innaka ‘afuwwun, tuhibbul-‘afwa, fa’fu ‘anni. (O Allah, You are Most Forgiving, and You love forgiveness; so forgive me). Say: Astaghfirullah al-ladhi la ilaha illa huwal hayyul qayyum wa atubu ilayhi It says in hadith, whoever says it seven times his sins will be forgiven even if he should have run away from the battlefield. Say: SubhanAllah wa bihamdihi Whoever says it hundred times, his sins will be forgiven even though they may be as much as the foam of the sea. Say: la ilaha illallahu wahdahu la shareeka lah lahul mulku wa lahaul hamdu wa huwa a la kuli shay’in qadeer. And say the many other forms of repentance that are prescribed by Allah. ALLAH HAS FULL ABILITY TO GIVE YOU ANYTHING YOU WANT! AND ONLY HE (ALLAH) HAS THAT ABILITY. The Prophet ﷺ said, “Verily your Lord is Generous and Shy. If His servant raises his hands to Him (in supplication). He becomes shy to return them empty.” [Ahmad, Abu Dawud, Tirmidhi] *****

The question, as put, is staggeringly simple to answer: like other texts, both influential and obscure, this text was not .. used widely or customarily received in the Catholic Liturgy. And that's it, no other reason; case closed. Now why 'Thomas' (as it currently exists) does not seem to have been used (frequently or at all) in the liturgies of the great centres of Church authority - and thus it is not reflected in the authors or writings of catholic orthodoxy, e.g. in its list of texts received as 'all scripture' - well, that is more complex; the briefest answer is that it was not well known, traditionally, as suitable for the divine service (being too 'late' in final composition, or not sufficiently trusted as a teaching tool). Text Criticism (supposed date, origin, witness, authority), Historical Criticism (finding a supposed 'real' author of the text/s or of the person being dealt with in various texts), et al, like all Higher Criticism forms, rest largely on subjective taste (the putative quality of a witness not the number of actual witnesses, the perceived hardness or brevity or complexity or primitiveness of the terms used, the available external evidence of other 'unrelated' or 'early' mentions, etc), which can be useful, of course, if taken as a matter for scrutiny, not of authority, of speculation, not evidence. Chiefly it is a jolly scholarly game of playing at Ockham's Razor, often misused or abused, having only one clear purpose in mind .. to get the results published (or better still disputed, requiring yet more academic discussion and publications). And that, even after all these centuries of critical form theories, remains the paradox of 'modern' Biblical Study programmes .. for they treat the reception, acceptance and handing-on of Sacred Tradition as if it were a puzzling word code, an undeciphered ancient text, or something dug up from an archaeologist's pit; it isn't, btw, it is 'life' as humans have tended to live it (never so neat as 'critics' would like to present it - or rearrange it). ;o)

One very interesting take on the origin of The Gospel of Thomas is that by Nicholas Perrin in "Thomas and Tatian: The relationship between the 'Gospel of Thomas' and the 'Diatessaron'". Perrin makes a convincing case that Thomas was originally written in Syriac, not Greek, because of the unusually high number of words or figures of speech (502, specifically) that are distinctively Syriac in nature. Some of these distinctive words and phrases even appear in other Syriac works, such as the "Odes of Solomon." He also shows rather convincingly that the puzzling order of sayings in Thomas can be explained by noting that at multiple points, the sayings collections follow the order of Tatian's "Diatessaron." The Diatessaron was a gospel harmony written by Tatian, which drew its material from Matthew, Mark, Luke, and John...all four canonical gospels. Therefore this would explain Thomas' dependence on the canonical gospels, which many others have noted. If this theory is correct, then dating Thomas becomes easier, because the Diatessaron was written between 170 and 175 CE. And if that's the case, then Thomas must have been created some time after that period---long after its supposed author was dead.

When most people think they are thinking, they are really only rearranging their prejudices. I have the advantage of knowing that’s what I’m doing. Everyone is introduced to certain prejudices by their parents and their friends. Most people are also influenced by the wider culture in which they live. The question, then, is whether to spend our time attempting to reinforce the prejudices we acquired when we were young or whether to study history while open to the possibility that there may be flaws in the worldview of our parents or our friends. It is a scary proposition to question what we were taught because - especially in the twenty-first century - it risks alienating our family or our friends if they (or we) fail to learn how to discuss such things without arguing. The subject of the relationship between Judaism and Christianity is especially difficult because of the different ways that people understand specific words - words that are almost impossible to avoid when addressing this subject. Religion Hebrew Israelite Jew/Jewish Christian Some people use the word “religion” to refer to traditions. Some people use that same word to refer to the beliefs, practices and prohibitions promoted by a religious organization. Other people use that same word to refer to the beliefs, practices and prohibitions of any individual - whether or not those things are considered traditional and whether or not those things are promoted by a religious organization. Some people use the words “Hebrew” and “Israelite” as synonymous. Some people - including yours truly - take certain statements by John the baptist, Jesus and St. Paul as indicating that a person who is an Israelite only in the sense of being a physical descendant of Israel (aka Jacob) or only in the sense of participating in certain religious rituals is not really an Israelite at all - i.e. only those who have the faith of Abraham, Isaac and Israel are truly Israelites. I confess that the instruction my parents gave me did not include the division of Israel after the death of Solomon. So I am sympathetic with people who don’t understand the origins of the words “Israelite” and “Jew”. It makes me cringe, however, when I hear someone refer to the people Moses led out of Egypt as “Jews”. There is no record - biblical or otherwise - of anyone referring to a descendent of Judah as a “Jew” until hundreds of years after the Exodus. Please let me propose an alternative to the question of how “Jewish” Christianity is or how “Jewish it ought to be. Maybe what we should be asking is whether we can accept as true Christians those people who practice specific rituals that were unique to the Hebrews before the birth of Jesus. I submit that there is a huge difference between the argument as to whether such practices are required for Christians (see Acts 15) as compared to the question of whether such practices should be prohibited among Christians. That second idea - that the instruction given to the children of Israel through Moses and other Hebrew prophets of antiquity should be prohibited among Christians unless expressly promoted by Jesus or the apostles - was developed during the centuries when believers in Jesus were trying to live alongside pagan Romans who hated the Hebrews. Are there aspects of traditional Judaism that are not biblical? Of course. Traditional Judaism is biblical as interpreted by rabbinical traditions. There are many professed Christians who consider Christianity to be biblical as interpreted by ostensibly Christian traditions. But if Christianity is a personal religion - not merely an institutional one - it is up to each Christian to study the biblical evidence for ourselves and each of us decide for ourselves whether the instruction through “Moses and all the prophets” (Luke 24:27) is applicable in the twentieth-first century.

The single most important thing to remember is that the Greek word for *Christ* is just a translation of the Hebrew word for *Messiah.* Thus "Jesus Christ" is the Greek way of saying the Hebrew for "Joshua-the-Messiah". Note that the real name of Jesus was always the Hebrew name *Joshua,* and the name Jesus we have today is just a mistranslation of the original name of Joshua. So the Greek "Christ" can refer to any Messiah at all, not just Joshua, and the Romans dealt brutally with several Jewish Messiah cults - or Christ cults - in the first and second centuries. The most important besides Joshua-the-Messiah was Simon bar Kochba-the-Messiah, which in the Greek language would be Simon-Christ, and his second-century followers would be "Christians" in the Greek language just as much as followers of the Joshua of the previous century were "Christians" too. From the point of view of the Greek speaking Romans there was no important distinction between any specific Jewish Messiah claimant, and they would be unlikely to have the inclination to care - they were all just Jews following one of their various Messiahs to a Roman soldier. During the Roman supression of Simon-the-Messiah in the second-century, the Romans became so anti-Jewish that it was virtually certain that they were killing followers of both Joshua-the-Messiah (aka Jesus-Christ followers) as well as followers of Simon-the-Messiah (Simon-Christ followers). After that second century bloodbath, the followers of Joshua were very motivated to distance themselves from the Jews who had followed other Messiah claimants by downplaying their Jewishness. This is likely the fundamental reason why modern Christians use Sunday as their main day of worship instead of Saturday - instead of the _actual_ Sabbath as required in their holy text. Over the centuries following the Roman supression of Simon-Christ, the Jesus-Christ movement carved for itself a new Roman identity that wasn't explicitly at odds with the Roman Empire like the Jews were known to be. I find this explanation rather unconvincing. Take Paul for instance. He recognized himself as persecutor of those who accepted Jesus as the Messiah, suggesting very strongly that mainstream Judaism (at least its Pharisaic sect) understood early christians to be something very distinct. It wouldn't be terribly out of place to imagine that a similar dynamic would play out if someone within judaism declared himself the messiah today. His acclaim would not be universal and pretty soon lines would be drawn around those who accept this individual as the messiah and those who do not. Indeed, the orthodox-judaizers (for lack of better distinction) debate is something that played itself within the early church for a long time, and if we read Ignatius (or perhaps even Chrysostom) along these lines we have a clearer picture of what was going on. The split between Judaism and Christianity may have happened very early (Paul in his roman letters already seems to recognize a difference) in history, but the internal dialogues between the different groups within early Christianity as to the role of judaic rites and practices within this new religion may indeed have taken much longer to become clear.

The argument: "we shouldn't use the word 'cult' in a pejorative sense" is a strange one. For this to be sustainable you'd have to ignore the fact that language shifts over time , similar to your characterization of "religions" in other videos. Alternatively you would need to assert academic primacy in language use: "only academics can use words definitively". But in that case, "religion" itself should only be used by academics since (as Jonathan Z. Smith noted), "“Religion is not a native term. It is a term invented by scholars for their intellectual purposes and is therefore theirs to define. " Notice how often in public discourse 'religion/religious/etc. are weaponized in exactly the same way that "cult" can be used: to marginalize, differentiate the "other", and dismiss. Just read some of the comments in your videos or listen to Bill Maher. Words have a general use and specific, in-group use. It's in everyone's interest to maintain linguistic continuity (to promote society-wide communication), even while acknowledging the continual evolution of language. In-group specialized usage of words goes far in preserving language meaning since the group population is smaller than the general population. For this reason, calling another group "cult" within a specific group likely carries specific meaning for that group and playing the "academic definition" card has no salutary effect. It's meaningful to understand the semantic range of a word, including academic usage, but attempts at linguistic policing are misguided when herding cats is easier than herding word use. Unless there is thought-control of Orwellian proportions, the wisest course is to seek to be understood and to understand the individuals we are in communication with at any given moment.

But looking back at church history when Joseph Smith first founded the religion, I definitely would have considered it a cult much like some of the weird hippy communes that seem to worship their leader who tends to take advantage of their authority within their group. Ingredients: 2 ¼ cups All Purpose Flour 1 tsp Salt 1 tsp Baking Soda 1/8 tsp Ground Cinnamon 2 Eggs 1 tsp Vanilla Extract 3/4 cup plus 2 Tbsp of Unsalted Room Temperature Butter 2 tbsp Vegetable Shortening at Room Temperature ¾ cup of Granulated Sugar ¾ of a Cup of Brown Sugar 2 cups Semisweet Chocolate Chips Process, 1) Preheat your oven to 375 degrees. 2) Combine together the first 4 ingredients and set aside. 3) In a mixer bowl fitted with a paddle attachment, cream together the butter, shortening, and both sugars. Add the eggs and vanilla and mix together until all creamy and combined. Scrape down the sides of the bowl to make sure everything is mixed well. 4) Add the dry ingredients and mix just to combine. Add the chocolate chips and mix just to distribute them through the batter. 5) Using a small ice cream scoop, drop the cookie dough 2 inches apart onto an ungreased baking sheet and bake for 10 to 12 minutes, until lightly golden brown around the edges. 6) Cool for 5 minutes on the baking sheet then remove onto wire rack and cool completely. These are not your typical doughy and dense cookies. These are light, crisp yet soft, chewy and incredibly chocolaty. The cinnamon is not strong enough to detect right away it just makes the chocolate more intense. I promise that once you make these cookies, you will never stop making them because they are seriously addicting. Enjoy!Recipe By: Laura Vitale

Chocolate chip cookies Ingredients: 2 ¼ cups All Purpose Flour 1 tsp Salt 1 tsp Baking Soda 1/8 tsp Ground Cinnamon 2 Eggs 1 tsp Vanilla Extract 3/4 cup plus 2 Tbsp of Unsalted Room Temperature Butter 2 tbsp Vegetable Shortening at Room Temperature ¾ cup of Granulated Sugar ¾ of a Cup of Brown Sugar 2 cups Semisweet Chocolate Chips 1) Preheat your oven to 375 degrees. 2) Combine together the first 4 ingredients and set aside. 3) In a mixer bowl fitted with a paddle attachment, cream together the butter, shortening, and both sugars. Add the eggs and vanilla and mix together until all creamy and combined. Scrape down the sides of the bowl to make sure everything is mixed well. 4) Add the dry ingredients and mix just to combine. Add the chocolate chips and mix just to distribute them through the batter. 5) Using a small ice cream scoop, drop the cookie dough 2 inches apart onto an ungreased baking sheet and bake for 10 to 12 minutes, until lightly golden brown around the edges. 6) Cool for 5 minutes on the baking sheet then remove onto wire rack and cool completely. These are not your typical doughy and dense cookies. These are light, crisp yet soft, chewy and incredibly chocolaty. The cinnamon is not strong enough to detect right away it just makes the chocolate more intense. I promise that once you make these cookies, you will never stop making them because they are seriously addicting. Enjoy!

ok but now compare the amount of time it takes to make a quesadilla with store-bought tortillas and pre-shredded cheese (I love cheese of all kinds, do not get the hate for pre-shredded), even if you add some extras like grilled chicken, to the time it takes to make the gourmet one. how much is your time worth? because that adds to the "cost". not just time spent prepping your mise-en-place and cooking the food, but time spent washing up - this recipe isn't exactly a one-pan dinner, is it? yes, it tastes incredible, I've done it before. check out Kenji's recipe for a quesadilla with a shatteringly crisp crust. but 99% of the time I'm looking for a weeknight dinner that can be done in 10-15 minutes, and that's where store-bought is clutch, and that's what this video (and so many of Josh's videos) fail to take into account. if cooking is your hobby, if you don't mind spending three days on a recipe and having a pile of dishes to wash at the end, then more power to you. but Josh frequently falls into the same trap as every Food Network celebrity chef, which is that he's not cooking at home-cook scale, he's cooking at TV scale. he's more concerned with impressing people with flavor than making something realistic and easy (e.g. most Chef John, Adam Ragusea, and even Kenji recipes). do you know why the store-bought tortilla and shredded cheese taste nostalgic? because that's what your parents bought, because that's what they had the time to cook after working a 9-5 and then squeezing in their entire life around it. it's what you ate as a kid because it was practical. there are definitely ways to improve upon the basic store-bought stuff, but calling this cheaper - considering the amount of time and effort involved, even if monetarily it's not that much more per serving - is just backwards.

The first way I learned to make a quesadilla was even worse than the basic one he showed. Same thing, except microwaved. LOL That said, there's a technique thing I feel like mentioning, for anyone who is excited about making these. Josh shows a kind of strange method for assembling them: putting the fillings on only half, folding, buttering, then putting in the pan. I can't imagine why. It is soooo much easier/better to do it as follows: put butter in the pan (a lot), put tortilla flat in pan, spread cheese over the entire circle, then place other ingredients evenly (as if making a pizza). When the cheese has melted, fold it in half in the pan. What this does is a) you don't have to deal trying to transfer a floppy buttered half-moon of raw tortilla, with ingredients spilling out of it, from the cutting board to the pan, and b) it ensures the cheese melts first, and melts fully and evenly, and is on both sides so that it glues the sides together properly. I've never seen anyone make it the way Josh shows here, and it's really just not a practical way to assemble it, and will lead to worse results and more mess. Built it flat in the pan, ya'll

As Chinese, I'm amazed how RIGHT Josh did the spicy flavor pot. Just two really important tips about enjoying hot pot: 1. You need really THIN sliced beef or lamb to maximize the flavor. 2. There is actually a dipping sauce for hot pot: half table spoon of Tahini (sesami paste), 2 table spoons of peanut butter and a table spoon of sesami oil, blend well with some non-chili soup (or just hot water) till the whole thing becomes sticky but diluted. It would be the best if you can get some of the "fermented bean curd" in it, but it's optional. Last but not least, some chopped coriander and green onions.

Usually the Asian recipes on this channel are pretty scuffed, but this seems pretty solid... though it's hard to beat some premade hotpot mixes. There's a reason most restaurants and families around the world use hotpot mixes, with tweaks, instead of making it completely from scratch. The sauces used here is pretty basic, and it's missing some popular hotpot dishes though. Also, no to the rice. Nobody eats hotpot with rice. That's just weird. It's not common to eat rice with Chinese hotpot, nor is it common with Japanese hotpot. Koreans sometimes eat rice with hotpot but it's almost always saved until the end where they turn the remaining broth and ingredients into a fried rice. Vietnamese and Laos also don't eat hotpot with rice. Nobody eats rice with hotpot. In general, the point of the hotpot is to enjoy the ingredients, then if you're still hungry you finish with noodles which absorb the flavor of the broth and don't take a long time to cook.
There’s meat soo isn’t it a broth ???

Hotpot is indeed one of those meals everyone loves once they try it, but I agree it can seem quite intimidating. Every Asian culture has some form of this, but I recommend Japanese Shabu-shabu for the first timers to try making. The broth only has a few simple ingredients and doesn't require as much prep. The main differences is that Japanese style focusses more on the flavors and textures of the fresh ingredients, rather than the deep/rich flavors of the Chinese style broths. But like you said, there really are no rules.. We mix and match sauces and ingredients every time, which is almost b-weekly.

This take on hot pot was actually pretty good both in terms of adhering to tradition and a unique take. However, for dipping sauces, I would say the most important sauce for chinese style hot pot would be sesame sauce, or majiang. It's a mix of sesame seeds, toasted sesame oil, and a variety of other ingredients of your choosing ranging from fermented bean curd (jiangdoufu/"jiang tofu") to tianmianjiang to even miso, and puree'd in a blender. It's the consistency and color of liquid peanut butter, and it's almost a must have in hot pot.

It's a pretty famous all-you-can-eat hot pot, so I think in total we repeated everything (various meat cuts and vegetables) 3 or 4 times. He even made me take them to the same store again before they left Japan. All of this to say, nabe/hot pot is one of my favorite foods of all time. It's warm, comforting, and really delicious. If you don't have a hot pot/name restaurant close to home, please try the recipe! You will never regret it!

As a Chinese who grew up eating hot pot I RANNNNNNN when I saw the notification I'll update thoughts after watching the video Update: okay so he did the broth by himself which is A+ for effort bc we don't even do that! We just buy the base in a block/sauce form and cook it. However, he did add some twists that are not necessarily that authentic (e.g. mushroom powder). Food wise he's got cabbage and beef, but I wish he'd tried even more authentic ingredients, like tofu puff, lamb, enoki mushroom, white radish, lotus root, and if you're more adventurous blood curd and beef entrails. My favorite in the non-spicy broth is frozen tofu (you just freeze soft tofu and throw them in, literally) it will develop these honey-comb-like structures that soak up all the delicious broth, YUM! Dipping sauce wise, personally I just like to add condiments to plain Chinese-styled sesame sauce, like fermented bean curd, cilantro, green onion, chili oil, soy sauce, garlic chive blossom sauce, toasted sesame oil, and Chinese black vinegar if you like something tangy. The only issue I ever have is the per serving cost calculations. While I get the "you still have the bag of flour" argument, that doesn't change what the grocery bill looks like when you have to buy whole units up front. This is actually a really solid one for me because you might actually HAVE the majority of these ingredients in your pantry so the up front costs aren't astronomical, but that isn't true of many of the But Cheaper series. There's also the problem of spoilage- There's none here really, but in other But Cheaper you have to buy a bunch of something and only use a small amount of it, Josh calculates that as something ridiculous like .13c per serving, and then the rest is probably going to spoil because it's not like flour in that it can sit for a long time and it isn't a common ingredient like eggs where you can just use it elsewhere. I checked out the price breakdown and some things just aren't making sense to me. Checked in my local store (I live VERY close to Josh, same state and I think same city.): (ALL in USD) Assume you have: Spices, Ketchup, hot sauce, WS sauce, Mayo (I don't but let's give him the benefit of the doubt here) 4 chicken breasts (Store brand) - 11.92 2 cups (473ml) buttermilk - 1.00 3 cups (450g) all-purpose flour - .95 2 quarts (2L) vegetable oil - 6.96 2 green onions - .44 1 lemon - .64 4 cloves garlic - .62 1/2 head green cabbage - 1.57 5 medium russet potatoes - 3.85 = 27.94 For his, he somehow got 13.58 for all the same items and he never accounted for the 2 liters of veg oil you have to buy to fry all this in. So my costs will be AT LEAST twice per serving what his are, and as it happens I don't have mayo handy so it'll actually be higher. TLDR I wanna know where he's finding 4 chicken breasts, of any quality for 5.09. Because it isn't Austin Texas in March 2022.

Gordon Ramsay clearly says "Crab Benedict" (0:22 & 2:47) both times that he identifies his dish. In my opinion there is a big misunderstanding about the idea that Italians have of food. As an Italian, I don't need an invitation to open my mind about Zanzibar pizza, simply because I know that if a food is prepared with care and love, choosing local products, and cooking on the spot, the result will surely be good. The problem is that we Italians give food meanings that go beyond simple nourishment (I don't think we are the only ones, anyway): for us food is linked to family, socialization and hospitality, so if one reinterprets the pizza is fine (although he might call it chapati), if he tells me mine sucks compared to yours, well that's a little offensive.

I have no idea what valid justification there could possibly be for calling any round open-faced sandwich pizza. Not everything with a slight superficial resemblance to pizza is pizza. But if Italians are willing to accept pizza bianca as pizza, which is simply bread with nothing on it, then anything can be called a pizza. You don't need any ingredient, not even bread. I guess pizza in the loosest sense really is just an open-faced sandwich of any type. And then as you move to a stricter definition you get closer and closer to traditional pizza, to a pizza margherita. I love and sometimes make Neapolitan pizza but I like looser pizza styles as well and can even enjoy weird borderline pizzas like a Zanzibar pizza of fresh fruit on an unleavened flatbread. Ok, the debate between Ronaldo and Messi will never end, I will tell you at the end of this comment who I believe has done better, and who is the current best and who will become the best. The reason this will never end, is because there is always a counter argument, and new arguments start more counters. Ok, so here are the arguments and how fight back against them. All the counter arguments are true, I have spent hours on researching these two players. Fact 1: Messi has a higher goals per game ratio. Ronaldo counter: - Cristiano Ronaldo has scored more goals than Messi in his career - Cristiano Ronaldo has scored more goals than Messi in La Liga - Cristiano Ronaldo has scored some goals in the EPL, the hardest League to score in -(Supposed fact) Messi scores more goals per game because he has the best midfielders in the world assisting him: Xavi and Iniesta, this is why he doesn't score as many when playing for Argentina Messi's counter to Ronaldo's: -If Messi had played as many games, he would have scored more goals -Cristiano Ronaldo has scored more in La Liga only because he played there when he was his best, he wasn't scoring as much when he STARTED in Sporting CP and Manchester United - If Messi was in the EPL, he'd beat the defenders as well, as you can see in the Champions League. - Messi has Di Maria on his team, who is also a world-class assister Fact 2: Ronaldo is a winger, why is he scoring almost as much as messi? Messi counter: - His position says he is a winger, but he always shifts into the middle and always swaps wings - Why is Messi, a player who plays more of a striker in the centre-forward position giving more assists than Ronaldo? Fact 3: Ronaldo is the more complete player, as he can use his head more effectively, has a better weakfoot and uses skillmoves Messi's counter: - Messi is better at some things, Ronaldo may be the faster player, but on the ball, Messi is definitely faster. Messi is also a better dribbler and has better vision which he uses for key passes - Messi does not need skill moves, as he can use his dribbling and speed to get past Ronaldo - If Messi, someone who does not use his head much, has a weaker weakfoot, and does not use skill moves scores more goals per game than Ronaldo, then he clearly is better Fact 4: Fifa keeps sucking Messi's dick. There are no counter arguments for this one because it is true. At the world cup, Messi was clearly not the best player, yet they still decide to give him the best player award. Messi is on the cover of the past couple fifa editions. Fifa 15 supposedly rates players by their performances from the past 365 days. Last year, Ronaldo was clearly better, why is Messi still higher, but has been downgraded by 1 to become 93 and Ronaldo has not been been given an upgrade? That's because Fifa keeps sucking Messi's dick, supposedly, that is why Messi has won the Ballon d Or more. Fact 5: Messi is younger, he will become better than he is now and will clearly become better than Ronaldo. Ronaldo's counter: - By the looks of it, it does not seem Messi is getting better, but Ronaldo is. My Opinion: I believe Ronaldo and Messi are god-like players, there is no counter arguing against that, however, one of them has done better than the other, and for the future, I believe one of them will become better than the other. Who I believe has done better in their career: There is no doubt Messi has clearly done better, he has scored more goals per game, assisted more and would most likely pass Ronaldo's goal tally if he played as many games. He has won the Ballon d Or 4 times, and is more often perceived to be the better player. Who I believe is better now: This is more obvious than who has done better in their career. Ronaldo is currently killing it with back-to-back hatricks and doing more than Messi. Ronaldo has currently scored 17 goals in 11 league games, whist Messi has scored only 7 in 9 League games. Who I believe will be better in the future: This is clearly a prediction, I believe if Ronaldo keeps going by the looks of it, he will expand their gap between their goal tally, and win more Ballon d Or's and eventually become better than Messi. But we just have to wait and see. Thank you for reading this, as I spend so much time and effort in researching and trying to get this argument finished once and for all. There is no doubt that Messi and Ronaldo are phenomenal players, they are often compared, and I hope this comment will end the debate once and for all. -Yani

Television footage of the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami showed an eight-year-old boy survivor named Martunis wearing a No. 7 Portuguese football jersey who was stranded for 19 days after his family was killed. Following this, Ronaldo visited Aceh, Indonesia, to raise funds for rehabilitation and reconstruction.[310][311] After accepting undisclosed damages from a libel case against The Sun newspaper in 2008, Ronaldo donated the damages to a charity in Madeira.[312] In 2009, Ronaldo donated £100,000 to the hospital that saved his mother's life in Madeira following her battle with cancer, so that they could build a cancer centre in his native island Madeira.[313] In support of the victims of the 2010 Madeira flood, Ronaldo pledged to play in a charity match in Madeira between the Primeira Liga club FC Porto and players from Madeiran based clubs Marítimo and Nacional.[314] In November 2011, Ronaldo donated a pair of his football boots to be auctioned by Real Madrid's 'Clasico' network. They were sold for £2050 with the proceeds going to fund schools in Gaza, Palestine.[315] In May 2012, Ronaldo and his agent, Jorge Mendes, decided to fund a pioneering treatment for a nine-year-old boy when it seemed that there was no hope left for the child, who has been battling cancer since before his second birthday.[316] In November 2012, Ronaldo sold the golden boot he had won in 2011 for €1.5 million and gave the money to fund schools for children in Gaza.[317] In January 2013, Ronaldo became Save the Children's new Global Artist Ambassador, in which he hopes to help fight child hunger and obesity.[318] In March 2013, Ronaldo agreed to be the ambassador for The Mangrove Care Forum in Indonesia. The black dog (depression) has a sibling. He tends to hang around me. He is named anxiety. And sometimes, he attacks me out of nowhere. It brings me to the ground and worries people. They ask what's wrong, but I never have a straight answer. I asked for help. But never got it. Anxiety hasn't been beaten yet, but maybe he will someday. But all in all, that's wishful drinking. And in my case, all you need is a friend to try and help hide the feelings. But things won't always go your way. When a friend can't help, I just have to remember that alcohol was always there for me. It drowns the dog. Leaving me with an even more depressed black dog. I try to drown him too but it doesn't really work. It only makes it worse. Depression tries to get revenge sometimes, and attacks me. But his brother somehow always comes back. So I try again. But that's what I'm worried about. And I'm not paying mind to the other problems forming. Eventually the problems get so bad, I give up. The only answer seems to be a knot hanging from the ceiling. Or a gun in my hand. Or pills in my gut. But their will always be a friend. To help you along. They might not realise it, but they could call themselves heros. They saved your life, and you don't know how to repay then besides do something you haven't done in a long while and.... Smile.

Also, *2 meters* ( _the minimum_ ) for social distancing, not one. It's my opinion that storing the mask in a sealed air-tight bag (like a "ziploc") is a _bad_ idea. That provides a stable moist environment for cellular growth. I believe that storing it in a heavy (sturdy, thick, etc) paper bag is a *much* better procedure. After thoroughly cleaning the mask with soap and water, rinsing it, and letting it air dry (or putting it in the dryer with your other laundry), put the mask in the paper bag and close the bag well by rolling or folding up the opening. Store it in a cool dark place (perhaps in a basement cupboard if available). This will allow the bag to absorb moisture from the mask, inhibiting the growth of nasties. If you have any of those desiccant packets (the little packets of sandy stuff that say "DO NOT EAT" that come with some products to keep them dry) then I would put them in the bag as well, to further reduce moisture. Remember, the three vital elements for germs to grow: *Moisture* , *Warmth* , *Food* ("food" being virtually anything organic).

*not having a proper period in over two years* *sweats profoundly* ⚠If you don't want to read this, don't go beyond this point, I'm not forcing you⚠ So I have a bit of an explanation on my end, but don't have a solution for this situation aside from seeing a gynecologist So as I've mentioned, my menstrual cycle hasn't come properly in over two years (basically the summer before covid hit was when it stopped) the large gaps of the cycle ended up being hereditary from my mom since she used to not have it for 6 months in her mid-teens, and that started when I was 15. It would be 6 months twice, then a year, and now two years for the gaps. And before 15, my menstrual was normal, it would come about once a month, but at the most 7 days later from a month. I freaked out when I didn't get it a month and a half later when I was 15, but my mom thought it was just late, even though I was hoping it wasn't pregnancy (it wasn't). 2 months went by, and I still freaked out, but not as bad, I actually felt great not dealing with it. 6 months rolled around and it definitely threw me off seeing it again, but it was a normal 7 days at most. It never came back until another 6 months, etc. SO! Now not having it for over two years, no signs of pregnancy, it feels nice, but it shouldn't be this way. Here's actually the issue I'm dealing with right now... ⚠This is where I'd suggest stopping unless you have some advice for this situation⚠ Usually, pee is normal, but during the menstrual, it's red (obviously) and the menstrual stains your clothes the majority of the time if you aren't covered properly. I actually still stain some of my clothes, but it's usually when I really need to use the restroom, and that pressure to try holding it in shows that I do stain my clothes a bit, but when I pee, my pee is normal. I've showered and actually would clean around there and inside, and there's actually blood inside when I clean it, but it never comes out, like it's trapped there unless it's scraped or something. And here's the other thing (as embarrassing as this is, it's involved) when I use the... restroom that's not pee... when I wipe, it's bloody too, more bloody than when I wipe going pee (which there's rare cases when it's bloody wiping after pee) In the end, I'm still planning on seeing a gynecologist, but, if you guys have simple advice that's not too technical, I'm all ears since this is good not dealing with the monthly suffering, but I know it's actually bad for my body to not do that cleansing. If you read all this, congrats....... you now know about my freaking period problem 😅😓

This is the ONLY explanation I have ever seen that actually tried to provide any reason behind the purpose of shedding the lining every month. Every other program is basically "I don't know, we just evolved that way". In this video, they describe it as a self-defense mechanism to protect against "bad embryos". The problem with that is, some bad embryos still attach and continue to survive for a lot longer before ending up as a missed miscarriage or whatnot or get all the way to birth and then die shortly afterward, so it isn't a foolproof method of weeding out bad genetics. I think the "bad embryo" theory came about because it's actually the lack of hormone signals that causes shedding. I'm guessing they thought this up assuming that's how they think the body detects a "bad embryo" by it failing to send proper hormone signals being on par with a non-fertilized egg that sends none; that "good embryos" hit a hormone threshold required to keep developing. If this were the case, they could have made a mention towards connecting it to solving the reason behind spontaneous miscarriage, but they didn't. I've also never heard of the endometrium lining making it more difficult to allow implantation nor that it causes a feedback loop of more aggressive implantation in successive generations. I had thought this video was initially going to say that menstruation was just hormonal "practice" for when the body needs to expel the placenta, but it unfortunately never connected that similarity. Whether or not a human gets pregnant, the lining is always built up then shed, some every month, others after 9 months (implantation just puts a temporary stay order). It's all just tied to hormone feedback loop based around the egg's lifespan. The lining that cycle is meant for that egg(offspring). When the egg (offspring) goes, so does the lining as it isn't needed anymore as its 'fulfilled' its purpose already even if it actually was never used. The body then repeats the process to create another offspring.

First, I was unaware that bats menstruated. Never would have thought that, if we are being honest. I know that they are considered mammals, but I wonder why they go through this process. Furthermore, it is interesting to know that in some countries a period is misunderstood. Which is actually really sad since this prevents girls from being able to go school or work. This misunderstanding is depriving young girls of a full education that they have a right to. I wish that these countries would be educated on this issue and some type of solution be put in place. I could not imagine not being able to go to school once every month because of something I could not control (or not having the proper products). Even in 1st world countries, I feel like periods are still slightly taboo. No one really talks about them; it is just something that is. I wish that society would get over this stigma so it can be a more acceptable and comfortable thing to talk about. Not even just periods, now that I think about it; women's health in general shouldn't be so taboo. I am not sure why people don't talk about women's health as much as they do men's but removing the stigma would be very beneficial to women as whole. Being open about your health allows others to learn and not be so afraid to talk to someone if they think something is wrong. Hopefully, one day the health of women can be discussed just as causally as those of men.

My 5cents for those with seborrheic dermatitis and frizzy hair: - Use warm or cold water, hot water can irritate the scalp and it opens your hair cuticles (it will dehydrate and look frizzy) - Leave the shampoo work for at least a couple minutes, meanwhile it is important to massage the scalp to stimulate blood flow (which is why it is ok to wash your scalp daily) - Avoid products containing silicone on your scalp!!! Many cases of dandruff are actually seborrheic dermatitis or folliculitis, and silicone will worsen them. The fewer products you apply when washing, the better. - Panthenol comes in many antifungal shampoos and it is enough to help condition your hair. - Your hair is frizzy and you can't stop using conditioner? Then use white vinegar mixed with 1/3 gallon (1L) of filtered water in a ratio of 1:7 to rinse your hair at the end and you will instantly feel how it relaxes (water with higher acidity will help close your hair cuticles and make it look smoother and less prone to breakage) - Damaged hair that needs treatment and dandruff? You can use 1-2 drops of argan oil (it is expensive but you only need that amount), massage the oil in your hand palms, then distribute it to your hair once it is dry without causing friction, and then use the tip of your fingers to massage the scalp. - And most important: let the sunshine on your scalp daily, not only you will enjoy an anti-inflammatory effect, but also has antifungal effects.

I think a helpful analogy is thinking about a garden. What happens when you have bare soil? Weeds are the first to arrive. People see them as annoying, but really they serve a purpose to protect the bare soil. over time as a more diverse group of plants come in, they will replace the weeds to return to a healthy, balanced, diverse ecosystem. Yeast in your body is the same. If you are lacking the balanced microbial ecosystem, the yeast will come in and take over to protect the “bare soil”. So really, the answer to dandruff is to restore a balanced microbial ecosystem, not fight and destroy the yeast. They will just keep coming back. The million dollar question is how do you restore a balanced microbial ecosystem in and on your body. The things that have been most effective for me, after trying many, many things, were the basics. Sleep well, eat well, be active, get sunlight, reduce stress.

Never use the same product twice if you suffer from dandruff, yeast is easy to remove, brush your hair before shampooing or better still in the shower but it this constant moving of your skins natural ph and the ph of the water and the product. I used to be a barber and ive only seen 3 things that work for dandruff or dry itchy scalp from dry skin in winter. 1. When you shower wet your hair thoroughly, Take a handful of Epsom Salt and put it on your head and massage the salt into your scalp GENTLY careful not to get into your eyes. Wet hair again and shampoo throughly with a MEDICATED shampoo. 2. Do NOT use the same shampoo for over 2 or 3 weeks, SWITCH out to a different shampoo often. Your scalp becomes immune to the same shampoo over time. Don’t use the MEDICATED shampoos all the time either every single day, switch often. 3. DO NOT touch your scalp with your fingernails, fingernails carry bacteria underneath them and can infect your scalp when scratching.

Short answer: Neutrogena T-Gel. Long answer: If you're like me you've tried a lot of shampoos that are marketed towards dandruff, yet for most of my life none of them have worked. The fact of the matter is that the yeast mentioned in this video is only one of several different possible causes of dandruff, so shampoos targeted against the yeasts may still not help you. I did eventually find ONE shampoo that gets rid of dandruff for me, though. Neutrogena's T-gel. It's literally the only product that has worked for me, and is recommended by the National Psoriasis Foundation, and people with Psoriasis can get extreme dandruff so a recommendation from this organization should be listened to. Use it everyday for a few weeks. It'll take a few weeks to kick in, and then you have to use it regularly but you can at least cut back to using it just a few times a week, but you'll be thankful for it. Also, put it in your hair at the start of the shower and leave it in for a few minutes before you rinse it out. It doesn't smell pleasant, but if you follow it up with like a mint conditioner afterwards you'll be fine. I bothered to write this long comment because I had BAD dandruff and I want to help anyone else out there who was like me. The active ingredient that makes it work is coal tar extract, which accoeding to Web-MD, "belongs to a class of drugs known as keratoplastics. It works by causing the skin to shed dead cells from its top layer and slow down the growth of skin cells. This effect decreases scaling and dryness. Coal tar can also decrease itchiness from these skin conditions." You can look up other products that use this but Neutrogena T-Gel is found practically anywhere. It's in a box at the store so just look out for that.

I found this to be informal but I believe they glossed over the facts of how diet, primarily vegetables and fruits, and the avoidance of almost all animal products, is crucial to avoiding a heart attack. At the beginning they mention how old age is a factor but they fail to explain why, and this begins some problems and may raise fallacies from their explanation: 1. This fails to explain that a heart-attack is not a natural occurrence, and in fact is a problem in countries that have a high rate of meat and animal product consumption, whereas in populations with low meat and animal product consumption, heart attacks are almost non-existent. 2. They fail to mention that the plaque formed in our arteries is because of cholesterol consumption along with saturated fat, in which cholesterol can only be obtained through animal and animal product consumption, apart from our body creating our own cholesterol which is all we need in cases apart from patients who do not produce enough cholesterol on their own, which are very few cases in the populace. And 3.This fails to explain that there are heart attacks occurring in middle-aged, or younger populations today than they really should. They fail to mention the correlation of how chicken is now being linked to obesity, and obesity, as we know, greatens the risk of heart attack. Somehow chicken is still mentioned in it's consumption to avoid heart attacks though. The other reservations I have are that, although they did a great job in explaining the processes of surgery, this video points much towards surgery, technology, and pharmaceuticals as being basically the most effective means towards dealing with heart attacks. Although surgery and technology has allowed us to save patients who have had heart attacks already, as I had earlier mentioned, prevention of heart attacks is very reachable through a diet very low or non-existent in meat and animal product consumption, and pharmaceuticals, although they can greatly help mitigating risks of another heart attack, they have their own risks associated with taking pharmaceuticals whereas eating a healthy diet high in fruits and vegetable/legume consumption has no risk associated and can stop a heart attack from occurring once again or at all. This video does not do diet justice and therefore does not inform to the extent that they could about how avoiding heart attacks are some of the most basic actions we can participate in, this goes along with how fruits and vegetables are slightly mentioned, but legumes and beans, which would otherwise replace the meat consumption of American diets is not explained whatsoever. The last piece of diet in which they failed to explain is that eggs, which are high in cholesterol and thus linked to the plaque build up of our arteries, should be avoided in order to prevent hypertension and heart attacks. Other diseases that can be obtained through animal product consumption such as fish and chicken are not mentioned as well but once again, this video was informal in explaining the process of a heart attack and the process of surgery associated.

Reading the comments made me want to share my story too. I’ve had about 3 major panic attacks in my 25 years but my last attack was my worst. It lasted about an hour or two maybe more and it worried my family so much that I ended up in the hospital at night. The doctor said it was a panic attack but I already knew because I had researched before when I had my first attack. Earlier in the afternoon I went to see my friends and we smoked weed in their car. I’ve been a frequent smoker for years and never had a problem until then. I drank an energy drink before meeting up with them. I’ve been stressing over everything in my life, it’s been the worst I ever felt, my grandma passed away from cancer, my car broke down again, I was fighting a court case, I lost my job from Covid and was unemployed. My anxiety was overflowing and I bottled up everything. My panic attack started when we were driving and smoking, I lost my phone a few days ago so I couldn’t even keep myself from overthinking. My friends helped me calm down I felt like I was a burden to them, but they reassured me I wasn’t. My friend parked the car and I stepped outside the car for some fresh air. My heart was jumping out my chest and I felt a sharp pain in my chest. I felt like I couldn’t breathe. I felt like I was dying from the inside out, like I was sinking with no way out. I was looking up at the sky asking myself “what’s wrong with me?” , “why am I like this?” , why can’t I just be normal?”. My best friend who is like a brother to me stepped out the car and hugged me. He told me “everything’s alright you’re gonna be alright”. It was cold outside and snowing so we went back inside the car even tho I felt trapped in the backseat but I asked my friend if I could hold his hand while we all talked to help me relieve my stress and make me feel better which I did. I did feel better after but I asked them if they could take me home so I can feel more comfortable. I went home and stayed in my room. I don’t know what happened but it happened again. I ended up calling my family and they drove me to the hospital. Now I stopped smoking weed because it made my anxiety and stress worse. I stopped drinking energy drinks and lowered my caffeine intake. I decided to open up more about how I’m feeling because I’m only human. I stopped having panic attacks since then but I still worry about it. My point is surround yourself with friends and family who understand and want to understand what’s happening with you. Talk to them and do things that make you truly happy. I focus on my music whenever I feel like I’m dying and I’m trying to better myself.

From someone with anxiety,here some tips to stop a panic attack: The “Five things you can see” thing works pretty well. Try it for sure. If you have some gum or even better,a mint,pop one in your mouth. Focus on the sharp,refreshing flavor and not the fear. If tears start coming,and you get that annoying ache in your throat and you KNOW stuff is about to go down,hold your breath,count to 5 think of your favorite song,curl your tounge,tap your toes. Do anything to stimulate your hands,feet and senses reason: activating all of your senses and body parts will give you many things to focus on and not the fear. Unless you get sensory issues in which case…. Get up and take a couple laps around the area. Srry if that’s bad advice I don’t really get sensory overload so don’t know much about it. And those are things that worked on me. Everyone develops they’re own ways to stop panic attacks in the end of the day tho I suppose

I had panic attacks and suffered from unrelenting anxiety for almost 2 years after I gave birth to my child. I have since completely recovered. I want to share the following tips: 1. Complete recovery is definitely possible; 2. Seek professional help asap (there is no shame to admit that you need help. Seeking help for emotional issues is no different from going to see a doctor when you suffer from physical ailments. No one feels ashame to see a doctor for a cold.) CBT helped me tremendously; 3. Many emotional issues have biological causes, such as hormone imbalance; 4. Take your time to seek out a therapist that is a good fit for you. Personally, I have consulted more than 5 professionals until I found the right one for me. 4. Never gives up! There is light at the end of the tunnel! Even though at times you may doubt it. I certainly did. But, have faith you will come out on top. 5. I am not afraid of, and I don't worry about a reoccurrence because I have learned the mechanism to deal with it if it ever pops up again. I hope these tips help. No matter what you do, do not suffer alone. There is help out there.
