It's really calming to know I'm not alone in this. I am 2 years panic attack free this August and now I often try to understand what made them stop. I used to have them so often, they were so scary, I hated having them in front of people because they kept talking to me but their voices were muffled so I couldn't understand what they were saying; my legs went numb, I was nauseous, heart went crazy, couldn't breathe... I remember one time I had a really big one which lasted for 4 hours and it happened on my birthday, kept thinking oh well, at least my grave stone will have the same dates lol. My last panic attack happened 1 day before I travelled to Austria with my mom to see her friends (I love mom, but she can be a bit chaotic!) I felt like the plane, the bus rides, the train - all needed me to be responsible, which made me have the first panic attack where I actually considered calling an ambulance. The whole journey I drew squares in my head, inhaled for 4 seconds, exhaled for 4 seconds, held my breath, listened to music so as not to hear the world around me. When we got there, I met my mom's friend, whose daughter had two small boys. They spoke German, I spoke English, so we couldn't really understand each other, but somehow that was okay. I remember drawing a hot air balloon for one of the boys and feeling a panic attack coming, then he came and said the German word for sun, which turned into laughter and us trying to mimic the sun. The feeling of unease went away. On the same day, we went down a path leading to a small body of water; the way down was quite steep, and a small kitten was following us. While everyone was happy, I was constantly anxious about the kitten falling off the hill, so I tried to guide her. The background faded, it was just me and this slippery kitten. At one point, I got angry, I didn't want to be responsible for her, so I just gave her to my mom telling her to look after her, that I can't deal with it. She said fiiiine, and then left her on a little bridge over the water, so the kitten almost fell. I rushed to get her, and I managed, which felt so odd. You know that feeling where you're pretty sure you can never save, only be saved? I knew this was a job I needed to do, nobody shared my sense of responsibility for this kitten, just like nobody seemed to share my uneasiness. And I guided her the whole way up again, where her owners said she always does this, going up and down that hill... I suppose I'm sharing this just to kindly say that it gets easier, somehow through things you don't expect. If mid-panic it doesn't feel like it, it will change. You will change! I think seeing innocence in the world, realising responsibility is needed but not meant to be perfect are good things to carry with you. That day, my panic attacks just stopped. I hope one day they stop for you too. I'm not sure if they'll come back, but if they do, I'll just draw squares in my head and mutter the German word for sun.

I was diagnosed with panic disorder and generalized anxiety several years ago. I have experienced all of the symptoms here many times and I was hospitalized several times when I was younger due to reoccurring traumatic events related to love relationships. It reached it's peak in my 20's. The worst of it was developing a vaso-vagul disorder and tachycardia, which would cause me to pass-out everyday whenever I experienced depression or anxiety. It felt like I had discovered the bodies natural self-destruction mechanism. It became dangerous when I passed out and punctured my chin on the side of a desk, which required stiches. I'm glad it wasn't my head. I wasn't taking care of my body well (smoking and drinking to escape the pain), and thus the mind, spirit (nervous system) and soul (emotional memory in the body) suffered like a chain reaction. Medications didn't work well for me, and neither did overly controlled therapy, although I do advocate for some sort of therapy and have definitely benefited from it once I found the right therapist. Doctors couldn't figure out what was wrong with me. All this changed when I stopped thinking someone else was going to save me, or that there was a miracle cure like a certain drug or escape route to make the pain and suffering go away. I took charge of my self through healthy diet and fitness, coupled with reading about different spiritual paths and philosophies which gave me discipline, without the shame of others directly telling me what to do with my life in the modern moment. I spent more time outside in nature away from society, social media, and the need to fit in all the time or be compressed by the judgements of others. I learned breathing techniques and yoga, which I practiced alone to find my own calm center without judgement of others. I managed all things addictive and gradually cut them out if they made me too overly attached to my pain and suffering. I found "the warrior's path" and fought my own demons head-on. Through all that work I can safely say that I am not perfect. I still suffer anxiety, depression, and the pain of life at times. I am a lot stronger though, and better able to coup and manage it through my knowledge and experience I have gained by staying in this world and greeting each new day with curiosity. I also know that life is full of pain and suffering for every living thing. It is part of the deal. Even the most privileged and comforted beings experience pain and suffering at some point or other. Being born is painful and so is dying. It is just the nature of life. It's not perfect, but it is beautiful and worth every breathe, when you are strong enough to detach in a healthy way from your own suffering and pain. Then maybe you'll have a chance to understand why you are here in this world.

One time I left the hospital crying because there is no explanation for every pain I have felt, and I went through the hardest depression in my life, it was a disaster and such a nightmare, I stayed a whole week in my room ( I live alone ) and I didn't even text anyone, and I kept ignoring every phone call. I didn't have the energy to do anything and I didn't even attend the midterms week. I felt that i will lose my mind and i will never be the same, I couldn't even sleep. The second day I had three panic attacks, I went to the emergency, and I felt that this will be my last day in my life. while I was in the hospital I booked a ticket to go back home and I withdraw my scholarship. My depression really controlled me to change all my dreams. I am getting now, but the only thing I regret is that I kept many things in my heart when I could express them. The most interesting thing is that right now I really knew my purpose in life. I will quit engineering, and I want to be a psychologist to help people live their best life. I had anxiety during 2020, but I was lucky enough to have such incredible, supportive, amazing friends and family who let me talk to them and comforted me through it all. Now it's almost 2022, and my anxiety is gone! Of course, I might get a little more nervous about something than other people will, but I'm still young, so there was enough time to do something about it. I had a total of only two panic attacks during that time, and both times I was extremely scared of dying. I thought I was going to die and those thoughts wouldn't leave my mind. So I started to take care of myself. Every time I looked in the mirror I'd think nice things about myself and what I saw in the reflection. I remember when the attacks happened, I'd always think "This too, shall pass" and start to feel a little better. I think both times my attacks happened it was because of a lack of sleep. The first time it happened I had no idea what was going on so I locked myself in the bathroom and texted my friend about what was happening, and he comforted me through it. The second time it was a smaller attack and wasn't as scary because I knew what to do and knew what was going on this time, but either way it's still a fright. My attacks didn't last the whole day, only for a few minutes or a little longer, but I would still be a bit shaken up for the rest of the day. You all are so strong, and I believe in you. I made it, so I have no doubt that you all will too. I'm forever grateful to everyone who helped me with my anxiety, so I want to help people with theirs in return. I'm the mom/therapist friend, so if any of you ever want to talk, I'm here💜Stay strong!

I appreciated this video…I also have things to add. My panic attacks were reduced partly through therapy and medication. However, if you really want to keep them at bay in a lasting way, then do a course in EEG neurofeedback through your therapist’s office. Neurofeedback retrained my brain without pain or side effects. I rarely have panic attacks now. The other key? Significantly cut down sugar and caffeine intake. Diet is key, because your gut and brain are continually talking with one another. Medications are great for putting out the fire of a panic attack. That’s not as handy as stopping them from occurring for a long, long time. I carry my medication the way I carry car insurance paperwork in my car. I don’t expect to use it all the time. I just need it if I’m in a wreck. Lastly, in the moment a panic attack is happening, trust your breathing to get you through it. When you feel the panic creeping up, focus on SLOW, abdominal breathing, for several minutes. Really feel your belly pushing out. That deep, slow breathing will restore proper airflow to your brain. That will calm the body. You’ll probably yawn—a great sign. What’s often occurring in a panic attack is that we are holding our breath. After awhile, that feeling of creeping panic became a cue that I’m not breathing slowly and deeply. A little while after that, the feeling in my brain didn’t scare me so much because I knew how to beat it. Also, do yoga, take walks, and eat your greens.

I suffered from Panic Attack Disorder for 2 months when I was 14, I behave like a 5-year-old who wanted to be with her mum all the time because I was scared of being alone since I knew I would think I was going to die. It was horrible, I could not be one second alone or I would start hyperventilating. During these 2 months, my mum had to call an ambulance 3 times because my heart rate would go too high and my breathing too that my legs would get numbed and my arms would start hurting as if I was having a heart attack. She would yell at me to be strong, so did my dad, we did not know what was happening to me or what was the cause of my behaviour. I took 2 MRIs to discard the idea that I had something not right in my brain, and all the doctors would tell me that what I was experiencing were panic attacks, but neither my family nor I had heard of such a thing before. We are from South America, and mental health problems are not commonly talked about, nowadays it is thanks to social media. But it took me 2 months, 3 ambulances and 2 MRIs to finally go to a psychologist and talk about what I going through, panic attacks 24/7, I could not even sleep ...the psychologist diagnosed me with Panic Attack Disorder and gave me Cognitive Behavioural Therapy and the 5 SECOND RULE, after one month of getting used to starting to live my life BY MYSELF again was such a victory for me. I later found out more people have this disorder for years and cannot get through it, and it breaks my heart because for me those 2 months felt like decades. My parents were really harsh on me to get better, they would not listen to me when I WOULD TELL THEM TO STAY in my room, and I really believe they made me stronger, because it only took me one month to get back to my normal life and go back to school. They push me to go out in the world by myself again, they still cared about my well-being but I truly believe that if they had not been strong and push me to get back to my normal life, I would still suffer from this disorder. Maybe not smothering gave me the strength I needed to get out of that state, but maybe it would not work for everyone because not all people are the same. My parents being harsh on me worked, but perhaps that is not the right answer for everyone. After those two months and one month of recovering, I have not had a panic attack, I used to have scenarios where I would start having one but with the techniques I learned I slowly started to have more control over my thoughts and not enter the panic attack state where everything becomes blurry and getting out of it is hard.

Feeling lightheaded is for me the scariest symptom because you fear at any moment you'll pass out. Also the thoughts of death are recurrent during an attack. I have found that focusing on an object like a license plate while I drive works. Also breathe through your nose and don't take deep breathes otherwise you'll keep hyperventilating. I also fond that going outside for a long walk starts to slowly calm down an attack. I had severe panic attacks for 6 months, where I literally felt like I was gonna die. I believed it was triggered from stress stockpiled since my youth. At first I had a lot of trouble stabilizing myself and I would breakdown and go to the emergency couple times thinking I was going to die. After learning what it was I had to convince myself that the symptoms: Breathlessness, dizziness, loss of appetite, heart rate out of control, stomachache, palpitations, impending sense of doom; that these were all imbalanced chemical reactions from my brain. It wasn't easy. Like almost everyone I fear death, but after many sleepless nights, I almost embraced it, I just didn't care anymore. My faith in God helped tremendously through prayer. It would help take my mind from only focusing on the symptoms which would make me panic even worse. My advice is when you get bad episodes; convince yourself that you are not dying, but that you are experience a chemical imbalance from your brain that will pass. And also distract yourself or divert your attention from the symptoms to anything else; for me it was prayer or confiding in a friend or family member. If you do these things you may eventually be cured from panic disorder. I thank God im cured from this disease when there are people out there that have been living with it for years.

I have some pretty major anxiety, I think partially caused by a whole lot of things I've had to deal with. As a result of this, a lot of innocent-seeming topics and words are major trigger words for me and seeing a bit too much of it can send my mood spiraling down rapidly, overwhelming me with either a significant feeling of anxiety that prevents me from thinking about anything else, or a straight-up panic attack. As someone with autism, I find it very hard to fully grasp what I'm feeling, and for anxiety or panic attacks that's the same thing. I know that what I'm experiencing is bad, but I don't really know what causes it or even what it is exactly until I'm knee-deep into the problem. Sometimes I don't even feel it coming up and instantly land in the spike of the issue. I find it extremely hard to find help regarding this — not only do I find it hard to explain what I'm feeling (where the problem's coming from, what caused it in a particular instance, what emotions it makes me feel, where it makes me feel those emotions, how it makes me feel physically, what I'm thinking about, etc.), that sort of information, but also... I don't know who to go to to get help. I'm not super independent as I still live with my parents and they still manage most of my things as my autism makes it very hard for me to take care of that stuff, so if I went to a therapist (if I even managed to find one), they'd likely find out. I don't want my family to know, as I know they tend to react to things like that in ways that only make the problem worse, whether that be never leaving me alone, telling others about it or anything of the sorts. They don't know that I deal with anxiety and panic attacks regularly, but I'm definitely not planning on telling them.

Extra reading; there is no single 'meningitis bacteria'. Bacterial meningitis is caused by many organisms including but not limited to: Streptococcus pneumoniae (gives rise to pneumococcus meningitis and is commensal in a significant minority of people's throats), Neisseria meningitidis (gives rise to meningococcal meningitis, typically presenting with the non-blanching rash), Haemophilus influenzae (The B serotype gives rise to aggressive, preventable meningitis), Listeria monocytogenes (typically only affects pregnant women, neonates and occasionally the elderly) and Group B streptococcus (neonatal and elderly meningitis) and atypical causes like E.coli (which can come from a septic UTI) There are vaccines available for MOST of these bacteria (PCV, MenACWY + B, HIB vaccines), but not ALL (Listeria, group B strep, E.coli and a myriad of other atypical causes, not even including viral, fungal and protozoal causes like naegleria fowleri). Additionally, you may not be up to date with your vaccines, each is designed for a different 'serotype' of each bacteria (N.meningitidis has 5 in A, C, W, Y and B that you can vaccinate against), and depending on when you received it, you may not have full coverage, as some are newer than others. TL;DR, 1. Antivax is irresponsible and misguided, so don't be unknowingly complicit in it. 2. Track down your vaccination transcript and make sure you're covered. 3. Don't gun to get the pitchforks if someone has meningitis, many people will develop it from causes outside of vaccines coverage.

This is kinda misleading. Meningitis is an inflammation of the meninges resulting from an infection, whether bacterial, viral, or fungal. So a number of different nasties can cause it, including West Nile Virus, Listeria, and some strains of strep throat. My friend's dad almost died from meningitis after having the flu. It can even (rarely) come from non-infectious sources like certain cancer treatments and penicillin. Get *all* your vaccinations, folks, not just the big baddies!

Why is "risk of amputation" a so commonly used phrase? It makes it sound as though body parts just spontaneously fall off as a direct result of the disease (which rarely happens with some diseases, in which it is called "auto-amputation"). "Amputation" isn't the risk, it's the treatment. "Risk of tissue death in the limbs, necessitating an amputation in order to prevent the death of the patient" is more accurate.

I had a brain hemorrhage at the age of sixteen (the third instance, actually, in a series of brain hemorrhaging that began at the age of twelve) caused by a rare brain arteriovenous malformation, which caused many of these symptoms, making it an elusive and difficult to diagnose illness. The doctors kept jumping to the conclusion that I had meningitis, which is fair, considering I basically had all the symptoms of it, but also frustrating for me because I knew deep down it couldn’t possibly be meningitis considering I’d had two previous episodes of the symptoms that would eventually go away until the next bleed in my brain. I’m 25 and i think i might have asperger. It feels like something is missing in my brain, like someone cut a chord connected to my brain. I can talk to people and understand sarcasm and human emotion but i can’t form deeper connections and relationships and i’m always alone and barely go out. I only do so when i have to buy something. I used to have 4-5 friends (before my teenage years) i could hang out with anytime of the week but got bullied in 4th and 6th grade. After that i kinda changed and became the ”quiet kid” in class. 6th grade we change schools in my country and it goes all the way to 9th grade so it was a new class but i new some of them from my old school and one of them was my friend. Anyway after this happened my mentor/teacher always said to my parents that i need to interact in class more (because they grade that too) that i’m too quiet...anyway this followed me all the way through higschool. 10th grade. New school, new class, new everything. At this point i only spent time with my neighbour who joined me in 7th grade (here things gradually got better) and two people i knew from my soccer team since i was 8. I had basically cut ties with old friends etc. We didn’t text or talk at all. Anyway i spent about 2 months in my new school before i made the decision that i wanted to change school and subjects so they hooked me up at some economics high school. I thought it would be good for me to meet strangers and expand my social network because i felt like i had too. Having 1-2 friends wasn’t gonna cut it anymore. Not in high school. The moment i joined my new school and class was mid term so all the others got a bit of a headstart to get to know each other and form groups and friends. Some of them were already friends from before. I got the chance to introduce myself and they all seemed friendly and all. I remember 2 guys and 2 girls really made efforts to get to know me and be my friend but i was cold and rejected them inderectly without even knowing it at the time. So i was alone until school closed in summer and we were about to begin 11th grade. I felt uncomfortable and changed school again with new subjects. This was more of a nature science school. Lots of math and physics. Basically the future engineers and doctors go to this school but this meant that i had to do 10th grade over again so i was 1 year older than the rest of my peers. But same thing happened here. And it was a nightmare for 3 years until graduation. I didn’t make a hard enough effort to connect so i was the outcast. In the beginning i sat with them at lunch but as they were talking i couldn’t say a word. I didn’t know what to say. I thought they would ask me something but they didn’t. This was 1-2 months in. After this i ate lunch mostly alone or sit 1-2 chairs away from random people. If reading this you know how bad it is so i’m skipping it to the last part. Graduation day...i had do drink shit loads of beer and champagne just to cope with my failure. I didn’t have great grades and the awkwardness being around my class mates celebrating even though i ghosted for 3 years made me sick so i had to drink just to cope. I had not a single friend to take a picture with or to talk to. Just my family. And here i am the exactly the same as i’ve been all those years but with improvements. Ofc i can talk to people whenever i go to the store, dentist, doctor etc. but sometimes after talking for 1-2 minutes my brain feel like the useless small talk is done and i can’t think of anything meaningful to talk about so there’s an awkward silence in the room and then they ask me if i’m ok. I hate this part the most. I don’t hate the person, just the question. I didn’t know at first why they’d do this but i searched it up and people can apparentely think that you’re annoyed or don’t like them and thus your silence makes them uncomfortable and this applies to extroverts especially but this ain’t that lol. So nowadays i always have anxiety before an appointment because i feel pressure to talk and entertain them. That’s not me and don’t think that’ll ever be me but i defintely still need to improve my social skills because i need a girlfriend...but no one wants to be around a guy who’s boring and don’t talk on their own. It’s not that i’m insecure about myself or anything but like i said it’s like something in my brain that’s holding me back. Ever since i was 19 i’ve thought i had asperger but i’ve never gone to a doctor to be tested. The ones i ever talk or text too are my dealer or acquaintances. I wouldn’t call them my friends. We used to hang out maybe once a month. Sometimes once every 2 months. They’d write to me or i to them too just asking what they’re up too. Sometimes i got invited to go out with them and their friends where we went to the club. But i cut all ties with them after reflecting and processing my thoughts. My dealer too. I’ve been using drugs recreationally for the past 3-4 years to escape my lame life and escape my reality. When using i could be who i always wanted to be or anyone. I’m usually on my PC. Used to be a hard gamer in high school, only thing i looked forward too was get out from school and go home to play counter strike. It stimulated my mind. But after graduation i was 19 and needed a job. I was still living at home at this time so i got a latenight job. Was a bitch to sleep at day though but i got money so i didn’t care. I quit the gaming since i neither had time or energy to play. It was work, come home, eat, sleep, wake up, eat, repeat. This shit drained me. I’m a big fan of hip hop/rap and u know how they promote drugs. So it was around this time lean or purple drank became so popular world wide. Teens started drinking that and so did i. It makes you kinda relaxed and u get a great fucking sleep. So this was my new stimulation. I drank in my room, watching TV, Youtube or listening to music nodding. I became addicted before i knew it. Almost a year after i got my license it got so bad that i even drank before driving. I almost crashed my parents car on a bridge when picking up my sister from practice. I fell asleep for 2 second almost driving on the opposite lane. That’s when reality hit me and i got slapped by my mom and had to explain myself. That’s when they found out what i’d been up to. Stopped drinking lean and switched to alcohol. Now 20 years old. The age when u can buy booze in my country. What’s better than alcohol? It’s easy to access and it’s legal. I continued working at that nighshift place until i was 22. Sometimes i was slightly drunk at work but they wouldn’t notice because i had high tolerance and we work alone. Would usually have a couple of beers. Weekends it was the heavier stuff. 22 i quit my job and been up to no good since. 22 i started doing drugs. From weed, to ecstasy, to speed/adderall. Getting high was all that mattered. I could go 2-3 weeks without using. Like i said it was recreational use. 2g-5g i binged in 2-3 days. But then i got phsycosis and drug induced schizofrenia. I saw people that weren’t there and heard voices in my head and songs over and over again. It was terrible. It’s a miracle they haven’t kicked me out yet but it’s bound to happen soon if i don’t change. I thought the muscle damage causing growth was a myth. From what I’ve understood, there’s two different types of muscle growth, hypertrophy and hyperplasia. Hypertrophy is when your muscle cells grow, hyperplasia is when you generate new muscle cells to repair and replace damaged ones. You want hypertrophy, to grow your individual muscle cells, so having too much muscle damage can actually hinder your gains. This is even observed in several studies showing massive drop offs and even declines in muscle growth after a certain amount of volume, particularly with higher weight, lower rep work.

I would recommend squats and or leg presses on push day, and deadlifts and or back extensions on pull day. Chest press will be a good option as your major upper body exercise on push day, with seated rows being the main upper body move on pull day. Considering doing inclined and declined moves in addition to standard moves if possible. Keep in mind that shoulder presses are pretty much fully inclined chest presses, with chest dips being fully declined ones. For seated rows, fully inclined equals lat pulldown, and fully declined equals shoulder shrugs. Incorporating leg exercises into push and pull day makes it logical to make the third day in a three day circuit hybrid day. Hybrid day routines could consist of cable crossovers from a myriad of angles, and or to a myriad of focus points. Also, this might be a good day for ab exercises such as torso rotation and crunches. Also consider adding neck flexion and neck extensions somewhere in your routine. If you're doing squats and or leg presses on push day, in addition to doing deadlifts and or back extensions on pull day, it seems logical to do calf extensions and or calf raises on hybrid days; alternating between pushing with your toes and your heels should promote good activation levels in all calf muscles. One last note, adding “wood chops" left to right, right to left, and straight down on push days, and “reverse wood chops" left to right, right to left, and straight up on pull days might also help you maximize gains. As far as isolated arm movements go, I recommend tricep focused moves on push day, bicep focused moves on pull day, and forearm focused moves on hybrid day. It's worth noting that using a pronated grip tends to add focus to the triceps, using a supinated grip puts more focus on the biceps, and a neutral grip is more balanced. Furthermore, a wide grip puts more focus on the torso, while a narrow grip puts more focus on the arms, with a more neutral grip again being a more balanced option. It's likely a good idea to favor a neutral grip in terms of pronated and supinated as this tends to generate more muscle growth overall than a pronated or supinated grip, because it recruits many fibers in the biceps, triceps, and the brachialises that connect them, as well as the brachioradialus that connects all of these muscles to the forearm.

What Makes Muscles Grow? (Transcrição) Muscles. We have over 600 of them. They make up between 1/3 and 1/2 of our body weight, and along with connective tissue, they bind us together, hold us up, and help us move. And whether or not body building is your hobby, muscles need your constant attention because the way you treat them on a daily basis determines whether they will wither or grow. Say you’re standing in front of a door, ready to pull it open. Your brain and muscles are perfectly poised to help you achieve this goal. First, your brain sends a signal to motor neurons inside your arm. When they receive this message, they fire, causing muscles to contract and relax, which pull on the bones in your arm and generate the needed movement. The bigger the challenge becomes, the bigger the brain’s signal grows, and the more motor units it rallies to help you achieve your task. But what if the door is made of solid iron? At this point, your arm muscles alone won’t be able to generate enough tension to pull it open, so your brain appeals to other muscles for help. You plant your feet, tighten your belly, and tense your back, generating enough force to yank it open. Your nervous system has just leveraged the resources you already have, other muscles, to meet the demand. While all this is happening, your muscle fibers undergo another kind of cellular change. As you expose them to stress, they experience microscopic damage, which, in this context, is a good thing. In response, the injured cells release inflammatory molecules called cytokines that activate the immune system to repair the injury. This is when the muscle-building magic happens. The greater the damage to the muscle tissue, the more your body will need to repair itself. The resulting cycle of damage and repair eventually makes muscles bigger and stronger as they adapt to progressively greater demands. Since our bodies have already adapted to most everyday activities, those generally don’t produce enough stress to stimulate new muscle growth. So, to build new muscle, a process called hypertrophy, our cells need to be exposed to higher workloads than they are used to. In fact, if you don’t continuously expose your muscles to some resistance, they will shrink, a process known as muscular atrophy. In contrast, exposing the muscle to a high-degree of tension, especially while the muscle is lengthening, also called an eccentric contraction, generates effective conditions for new growth. However, muscles rely on more than just activity to grow. Without proper nutrition, hormones, and rest, your body would never be able to repair damaged muscle fibers. Protein in our diet preserves muscle mass by providing the building blocks for new tissue in the form of amino acids. Adequate protein intake, along with naturally occurring hormones, like insulin-like growth factor and testosterone, help shift the body into a state where tissue is repaired and grown. This vital repair process mainly occurs when we’re resting, especially at night while sleeping. Gender and age affect this repair mechanism, which is why young men with more testosterone have a leg up in the muscle building game. Genetic factors also play a role in one’s ability to grow muscle. Some people have more robust immune reactions to muscle damage, and are better able to repair and replace damaged muscle fibers, increasing their muscle-building potential. The body responds to the demands you place on it. If you tear your muscles up, eat right, rest and repeat, you’ll create the conditions to make your muscles as big and strong as possible. It is with muscles as it is with life: Meaningful growth requires challenge and stress.

Here’s what I do at the gym: the first day of going I find my complete max weight on bench press deadlift and squat. After that write it down in a notebook and take percentages. So you would start off with 40% of your max for five reps and so on and my notebook looks like this: 40% x 5 50% x 5 60% x 5 75% x 5 85% x 5 5 sets of 5 reps of 65% Do this and alternate workouts like do Monday deadlift, Tuesday run, Wednesday benchpress, Thursday run, Friday squat, and weekend rest. Even if your max is not high at all this will still work you to your fullest if your a beginner I recommend this.

Don't do that guys, use light weights first, concentrate on doing the excercise right, build a soild mind-muscle-connecten and when you can actually feel and target the muscle, then increase the weight. Choose a weight, so that you can do 8- 12 reps, 6- 14 is also fine, as long as you tire out your muscle. But only going for 1-3 reps will only increase strenght, not actually visible muscle mass. I completely disagree with Khabib that he has nothing else to prove. These are my issues with Khabib: 1. He had a total of 13 UFC fights in his entire career and defended his title only 3 times. 2. Of the fighters he fought, none of them were champions in their prime: He beat RDA before he had peaked, beat Conor after two years of inactivity (would have lost in 2015 against him), and beat Poirier and Gaethje who were weak contenders in an empty division. 3. He lost his fight to Tibau, who had 28 significant strikes to Khabib's 25, with a 32% landing rate compared to Khabib's 24%. 4. He ends his career with a total of 8 fights in the last 8 years, making him the least active champion in UFC history. After all, the rule is that you give up your title after one year of inactivity, so he did the absolute minimum to maintain his title and minimize possible losses. 5. His style is one of the lamest in the world because the UFC is meant to determine the best fighting style, but his strategy of pushing people into the fence and holding them there wouldn't work in a real street fight because his eyes would get poked out, so he's using some kind of cheap technicality to win fights with a fighting style that doesn't actually work in real life, defeating the entire purpose of the competition and why the UFC was started. 6. If he actually fought at the weight he walks around at of 185, he would lose to Israel Adesanya without much of a contest. 7. Even if he fought 15 pounds below his walk around weight and fought Kamaru Usman at 170 pounds, he would lose there too. 8. Khabib was brought up to avoid losses, and avoided fighting anyone like GSP or Anthony Pettis in 2014 to protect his record. 9. In the original days of UFC, to determine the best fighter in the world, Khabib wouldn't even be in the top 10 contenders, would get smashed, and no one would hear about him. Shrinking down to 155 pounds to fight small guys is an advantage that gives a special advantage to short guys like Khabib. Fighting a longer fighter like Jon Jones, he wouldn't stand a chance, even if both fought at 200 pounds, which would be easy for Khabib to make. 10. All in all, he feels like very much a paper tiger champion: a fighter brought up with barely any fights, who lost to Tibau, has a fighting style that doesn't work in real fights, who fought at an artificially low weight class with no good wrestlers or top contenders to be heavier than everyone else on fight night by 10 pounds, then vacated the title quickly to avoid losing. In the old days of the UFC, we never would have heard of Khabib because his approach only works at an artificially low weight class with no good wrestlers and he isn't actually as good a fighter as any of the big guys. Conclusion: Khabib Nurmagomedov barely fought, barely had any challenges, had a fighting style that doesn't work in the real world, ducked tough opponents, and fought at an artificially small and easy weight class because he would have been destroyed by real men. He is the most overrated fighter in UFC history, and did nothing to prove his greatness. Beating a 5'7" guy by weighing 10 pounds more than him and pushing him into the fence doesn't show greatness of any kind: it just shows that he can beat small guys with a lame fighting style that doesn't even work in the real world.

I had gone to watch this match in the stadium. When it was 2 runs required of 3 balls, we along with few people started to leave the stadium thinking that we lost this game. Fortunately there was a gaint screen in the passage where match was being telecasted and there was a 30 second lag. When we came near gaint screen we heard a big roar from the crowd in the stands. People stopped moving and place near gaint screen was blocked. We came to know about the wicket after looking at the gaint screen and there was mini roar in the passage. Now it is 2 runs of 2 balls. We here one more big roar from the stands and we wait anxiously to find out another wicket has fallen. There was another mini roar in the stands. Then after few seconds we here another big roar from the stands and this confirmed in our hearts that india has won. After historical moment is being telecasted in big screen, the crowd in the passage went mental. I remembering seeing few diehard fans doing full shastanga namaskar to MSD'S poster in the passage. I will never forget this experience.

To anyone who tells themselves that they are not beautiful, or looks at a model and thinks... "this girl is more beautiful ever be!" I want you to know that that's the way people look at you. Everyone (even the models) look in the mirror, and see something wrong with their image. Something that maybe no one else sees. All of us are guilty of not loving ourselves enough. We look in the mirror, and we see something that needs to be changed. Be it our weight, our hair, face, skin. I want you to know that someone out there looks at you and says "I wish I could be as beautiful as her". Maybe you don't see it, but they do. We're not all equal by society's standards. But who said they're right? I want you to do something for me. I want you to remember this, the next time you say anything negative about yourself. Now go look in a mirror And instead of pointing out everything you see wrong Point out what you find about yourself to be most beautiful. I promise This can change your life Because beauty is in the eye of the beholder.

THE 10 COMMANDMENTS OF INGROWN HAIR PREVENTION by WIZKER THOU SHALL NOT TAKE PREP TIME IN VAIN! You should be using a warm/hot water prep (5 mins). Then leave the shaving creme on for more than 3 minutes to really soften the hair. The hair stubble should literally fall away with little or no pressure at all. Pressing hard is the problem! Be gentle ya'll. HONOR THY PRECIOUS SKIN! Too many blades! If you are prone to ingrown hairs then you don’t need 3 or more blades. THOU SHALT NOT USE DIRTY BLADES! Using a blade that's been used way too many times. Yes, this one may be obvious, but be sure to keep your used tools as clean as possible. Soap and rubbing alcohol will destroy bacteria. THOU SHALT NOT PRESS! Pressing grabs more of the hair follicle and while this might get you a closer shave, it will also guarantee ingrown hairs. Don’t press too hard on the skin with the blade. A gliding, light touch is all you need. THOU SHALT NOT PASS! PASS! PASS! Too many quick passes with the blade in the same area. One pass per hairy area – going 1-2 inches downward at a time – will prevent ingrown hairs. Always shave like you might cause damage, not like your mowing the front yard lawn. THOU SHALT NOT COMMIT OVER SHAVING! Scheduling your shaves too often. For example: shaving on Monday and then shaving on Wednesday. This rule is hard to follow, especially if you have to shave for your career but if you are prone to ingrowns, try shaving with an electric clipper. The results are not super close but no one but you will know the difference. Ladies, try waxing. THOU SHALT NOT GO AGAINST THE GRAIN! Shave WITH the grain means shaving in the direction of hair growth (usually down, but perform a face map to be sure). THOU SHALT NOT CLOG! Use of skin/pore clogging cremes or lotions. These keep hairs from growing up. After a shave, keep your skin bare; let the tiny army breath, and allow those newly shaved, really small, microscopic hairs to grow out just in time for the next shave. KEEP THY SMOOTH SKIN FREE! Avoid super tight fitting shirts around the Adam’s apple (neck) and/or constricting fabrics below the waistline region. REMEMBER TO EXFOLIATE! Exfoliation removes excess layers of skin and prevents shorn hair from regrowing towards the skin and from becoming trapped beneath the skin. Brushing teases the hairs away. Get WIZKER for your face or body region and use as directed.

Nice nails are always a great pop of sexy femininity. Nothing too long or drastic but a surprising pastel nail extension or rich jewel polish adds a lot to the look. You always nail that. Pun intended. Additionally, jewelry is a great way to draw attention to certain areas. Necklaces emphasize the bust/cleavage even if the neckline only gives the tiniest peek (in my opinion the perfect sexy tease). Dangling earrings with a simple bun or updo look emphasize the sexiness of the neck and shoulders. Belts give sexy curves. When paired with a monotone outfits, bold jewelry makes the look. Picking up a single feature is really key and that's why sexy/naked outfits really fail because it's such a sensory overload.

I'm a huge fan of corsets, but let me just say waist trainers and corsets are not the same. A corset should never be elasticated or stretchy. Corsets, by definition, are shapewear that depends on boning to hold the shape, and laces to add tension to the waist (and only to the waist). This is super important - and why elasticated / stretchy fabrics are NOT corsets - they use elastic to squeeze you all over. A lot of corset enthusiast will try to say that steel boned corsets are the only "real" corsets or that you need a certain number of bones, but that's not true. However, do be wary of plastic boned corsets - a lot of the time, they're too flimsy to effectively use as shapewear. Corsets can be difficult to wear as underwear / shapewear, as the laces and hardware can be bulky. There are corsets designed with this in mind, but do be aware that not every corset is a good base for your outfits. Corseting regularly is a big deal, and you should think thoroughly about it before you commit. Waist training (corseting with the intention of reducing your waist semi-permanently over time) and tightlacing (corseting with the intention of lacing your waist 6+" smaller than its natural size) are forms of body modifications. If you're interested in corseting, I highly suggest you think about it as a body modification before committing. Lastly, corsets should be comfortable. I have three that I wear instead of medical braces (I dislocate my ribs regularly). This only works because the only point of tension is on the waist. If a corset compresses your ribs, your hips, or makes your back ache, or leaves you with bruises, it is not a corset for you. I highly recommend buying made-to-measure or fully custom, because, as before, corseting is a body modification. I have bought "standard" size corsets that have 4" of difference between the waist and hips, which is less than the average woman has. How can a corset accentuate your curves when it's less curvy than you are?

The only thing I don't really like with this video is the tips about shapewear. I do think shapewear is a great thing whenever you need to look fabulous, but I don't think anyone should wear it on a daily basis. Just like make up, and I'll explain why. The body you have without make up and without shapewear is your most natural version of your body. It's your "normal" you, in some way. But if on a daily basis you wear a lot of make up and shapewear, this better version of yourself becomes the normal you, and in contrast, your true you becomes ugly. Simply said: make up+ shapewear = ordinary and normal, no make up and no shape wear= uglier than the ordinary. If you don't wear make up often don't use shape wear on a daily basis, then the normal you is the simplest version of you, but the you with make up and shape wear is an extraordinary beauty. Simply said again, no make up-no shapewear = normal, make up+shapewear = bomb. I think it's important to remember that what should be seen by ourselves and by everyone as normal is the version of us without tricks. Because we are naturally born without make up and shapewear, and those extra thing should be kept as an extra that is just there to make you look extra pretty sometimes.

I just comb my almost dry hair over my head while bending upside down into a ponytail at about “unicorn angle.” I do NOT use a ponytail band or rubber band or bobby pins. Then I gently twist the ponytail from the middle to the ends. Then I take a rolled up washcloth and use it like it’s a roller. Roll from ends to scalp and secure with a claw clip, with front of claw over roll from behind and back of claw into hair on back of scalp. Wait 2 hours or until dry. Unroll and gently brush hair out, but leave scalp hair alone if you want some lift.
